center\"|[[2016 China Rally|CHN]]<br><small>C</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Tour de Corse|FRA]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally de Espa\u00f1a|ESP]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Wales Rally GB|GBR]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfdddf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Australia|AUS]]<br><small>2</small>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#eaecf0;text-align:left\" rowspan=\"2\"|{{flagicon|DEU}} '''[[Volkswagen Motorsport|Volkswagen Motorsport II]]'''\n|{{Flagicon|NOR}} [[Andreas Mikkelsen]]\n|{{Flagicon|NOR}} [[Anders J\u00e6ger]]\n|style=\"background-color:#dfdddf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Monte Carlo Rally|MCO]]<br><small>2</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Sweden|SWE]]<br><small>4</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#efcfff;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Mexico|MEX]]<br><small>Ret</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffdd9f;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Argentina|ARG]]<br><small>3</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Portugal|PRT]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Italia Sardegna|ITA]]<br><small>8</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Poland|POL]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Finland|FIN]]<br><small>5</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rallye Deutschland|DEU]]<br><small>4</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffff;text-align:center\"|[[2016 China Rally|CHN]]<br><small>C</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffdd9f;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Tour de Corse|FRA]]<br><small>3</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#efcfff;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally de Espa\u00f1a|ESP]]<br><small>Ret</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Wales Rally GB|GBR]]<br><small>9</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf;text-align:center\"|[[2016 Rally Australia|AUS]]<br><small>1</small>\n|style=\"background-color:#ffdd9f;text-align:center\"|{{nowrap|'''163'''}}\n|style=\"background-color:#ffdd9f;text-align:center\"|{{nowrap|'''3rd'''}}\n|- \n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n* {{Double-dagger}} \u2014 Team ineligible to score manufacturer points.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Volkswagen Motorsport]]\n* [[World Rally Car]]\n** [[Citro\u00ebn DS3 WRC]]\n** [[Citro\u00ebn C3 WRC]]\n** [[Ford Fiesta RS WRC]]\n** [[Ford Fiesta WRC]]\n** [[Hyundai i20 WRC]]\n** [[Hyundai i20 Coupe WRC]]\n** [[Mini John Cooper Works WRC]]\n** [[Toyota Yaris WRC]]\n* [[Group R]]\n** [[Volkswagen Polo GTI R5]]\n* [[Super 2000]]\n** [[\u0160koda Fabia S2000]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Volkswagen Polo R WRC}}\n*[http://www.volkswagen-motorsport.com Volkswagen Motorsport official website]\n*[http://www.wrc.com/en/wrc/news/november-2016/vw-in-numbers/page/4105--12-12-.html Volkswagen's four years in numbers] wrc.com\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box | before = {{nowrap|[[Peugeot 208#208 T16 Pikes Peak|Peugeot 208 T16 Pikes Peak]]}} | title = [[Autosport Awards]]<br />{{nowrap|Rally Car of the Year}} | after = [[Ford Fiesta WRC]] |years = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2016 World Rally Championship season}}\n{{Volkswagen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Volkswagen Polo R Wrc}}\n[[Category:World Rally Cars]]\n[[Category:Volkswagen vehicles|Polo R WRC]]\n", "name_user": "SJS114", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal season (2016)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volkswagen_Polo_R_WRC"}
{"title_page": "M\u00e1ximo Jerez", "text_new": "{{short description|Nicaraguan politician}}\n[[File:M\u00e1ximo Jerez.jpg|thumb|M\u00e1ximo Jerez monument in front of the Cathedral in Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua.]]\n\n'''M\u00e1ximo Jerez Teller\u00eda''' (8 June 1818 in [[Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua]] &ndash; 12 August 1881 in [[Washington, D.C.]], USA) was a 19th-century [[Nicaragua]]n [[politician]], [[lawyer]] and [[military leader]].\n\nHe is considered to be one of the greatest [[Liberalism|Liberal]] political thinkers in Nicaraguan history. He was a leader of the movement towards Central American unity.<ref>Gamez, Jose D., ''El Le\u00f3n del Istmo Apuntamientos para la Biograf\u00eda de M\u00e1ximo Jerez'', Guadalupe LTDA, 1989, Colombia.</ref><ref>\nWolfe, Justin. ''The Everyday Nation-State: Community & Ethnicity in Nineteenth-Century Nicaragua.'' Lincoln: The University of Nebraska Press, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-4818-2}}</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Francisco Castell\u00f3n Sanabria]], he participated in bringing to Nicaragua the [[Filibuster (military)|filibuster]] of [[William Walker (filibuster)|William Walker]] and on 31 October 1855 was designated Minister of Foreign Relations in Walker's provisional government, led officially by [[Patricio Rivas]]. He ran for the presidency in 1856, but no candidate obtained an absolute majority. By Walker's decision, provisional President Rivas summoned new elections on 10 March 1856, but countermanded the decree on 14 March, and broke relations with Walker.\n\nOn 23 January 1857 Jerez formed a dual Junta government with the Conservative [[Tom\u00e1s Mart\u00ednez]] and they acted jointly as Presidents of Nicaragua, from 24 June 1857 to 19 October or 15 November 1857.<ref name=\"mined\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009181920/http://www.mined.gob.ni/gobern15.php|title=Gobernantes de Nicaragua|date=9 December 2012|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n}}</ref> In his subsequent career as Minister Plenipotentiary of Nicaragua to [[Costa Rica]], he signed on 15 April 1858, the [[Ca\u00f1as\u2013Jerez Treaty]] that defined the boundaries between the two countries.\n\nIn 1876 he organized from [[El Salvador]] an expedition to overthrow the provisional government of [[Pedro Joaqu\u00edn Chamorro Alfaro]], but failed.\n\nIn the city of Le\u00f3n there is a statue in his honor.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Presidents and heads of state of Nicaragua}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jerez, Maximo}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan diplomats]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Nicaragua) politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nicaraguan politician}}\n[[File:M\u00e1ximo Jerez.jpg|thumb|M\u00e1ximo Jerez monument in front of the Cathedral in Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua.]]\n\n'''M\u00e1ximo Jerez Teller\u00eda''' (8 June 1818 in [[Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua]] &ndash; 12 August 1881 in [[Washington, D.C.]], USA) was a 19th-century [[Nicaragua]]n [[politician]], [[lawyer]] and [[military leader]].\n\nHe is considered to be one of the greatest [[Liberalism|Liberal]] political thinkers in Nicaraguan history. He was a leader of the movement towards Central American unity.<ref>Gamez, Jose D., ''El Le\u00f3n del Istmo Apuntamientos para la Biograf\u00eda de M\u00e1ximo Jerez'', Guadalupe LTDA, 1989, Colombia.</ref><ref>\nWolfe, Justin. ''The Everyday Nation-State: Community & Ethnicity in Nineteenth-Century Nicaragua.'' Lincoln: The University of Nebraska Press, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-4818-2}}</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Francisco Castell\u00f3n Sanabria]], he participated in bringing to Nicaragua the [[Filibuster (military)|filibuster]] of [[William Walker (filibuster)|William Walker]] and on 31 October 1855 was designated Minister of Foreign Relations in Walker's provisional government, led officially by [[Patricio Rivas]]. He ran for the presidency in 1856, but no candidate obtained an absolute majority. By Walker's decision, provisional President Rivas summoned new elections on 10 March 1856, but countermanded the decree on 14 March, and broke relations with Walker.\n\nOn 23 January 1857 Jerez formed a dual Junta government with the Conservative [[Tom\u00e1s Mart\u00ednez]] and they acted jointly as Presidents of Nicaragua, from 24 June 1857 to 19 October or 15 November 1857.<ref name=\"mined\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009181920/http://www.mined.gob.ni/gobern15.php|title=Gobernantes de Nicaragua|date=9 December 2012|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n}}</ref> In his subsequent career as Minister Plenipotentiary of Nicaragua to [[Costa Rica]], he signed on 15 April 1858, the [[Ca\u00f1as\u2013Jerez Treaty]] that defined the boundaries between the two countries.\n\nIn 1876 he organized from [[El Salvador]] an expedition to overthrow the provisional government of [[Pedro Joaqu\u00edn Chamorro Alfaro]], but failed.\n\nIn the city of Le\u00f3n there is a statue in his honor.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Presidents and heads of state of Nicaragua}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jerez, Maximo}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Le\u00f3n, Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan diplomats]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Nicaragua) politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%A1ximo_Jerez"}
{"title_page": "Raiden (Metal Gear)", "text_new": "{{short description|Character in Metal Gear}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Raiden (''Metal Gear'')}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n|name= Raiden\n|image= Raiden MGS2.png\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= Raiden, as portrayed in a promotional CGI render for ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]''.\n|first = ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' (2001)\n| last = ''[[Super Bomberman R]]'' (2018)\n|series= [[Metal Gear]]\n|creator= [[Hideo Kojima]]\n|designer= [[Yoji Shinkawa]]\n|voice= [[Quinton Flynn]]<br />[[Charlie Schlatter]] (''[[Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater#Subsistence|MGS3]]'' Secret Theater)<br/>[[Kenyu Horiuchi]] (Japanese)\n|motion_actor= Eiji Morisaki (''MGS2'') <br/> Takeshi Yoshioka (''MGS4'')\n|nationality= [[Liberian Americans|American-Liberian]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2012/11/22/metal-gear-rising-main-cyborgs-explained-alliances-weapons-and-abilities/ |title=Metal Gear Rising main cyborgs explained \u2013 alliances, weapons and abilities |magazine=[[PlayStation Official Magazine - UK|PlayStation Official Magazine]] |author=Hurley, Leon |date=November 22, 2012 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127213241/http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2012/11/22/metal-gear-rising-main-cyborgs-explained-alliances-weapons-and-abilities/ |archivedate=November 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n| family             = Solidus Snake (guardian), Rosemary (wife), John (son)\n|affiliation= [[FOXHOUND|Pseudo-FOXHOUND]] operative unknowingly employed by [[The Patriots (Metal Gear)|The Patriots]] (''MGS2'')<br/>Free agent (''MGS4'', Post-MGRR)<br/>Cyborg private military contractor (''MGRR'')\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Raiden'''|\u96f7\u96fb|lead=yes}}, real name {{nihongo|Jack|\u30b8\u30e3\u30c3\u30af|Jakku}}, is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] and one of the main protagonists of [[Konami]]'s ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series of video games. The character was created by [[Hideo Kojima]] and designed by [[Yoji Shinkawa]], and was introduced in the series as the main [[player character]] of the 2001 [[stealth game]] ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]''. In ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', Raiden appears to be a member of the U.S. special operations unit [[FOXHOUND]] and is participating in his first mission against terrorists. Despite coming across as a rookie, he is a young soldier who is later revealed to have been a Liberian [[child soldier]]. Raiden also appears as a supporting character in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots]]'', in which he is assisting the series' protagonist [[Solid Snake]] in his fight against [[Revolver Ocelot]]'s forces. He is also the main character of the [[hack and slash]] game ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'', in which he is dealing with his past and his present life as a combatant who faces enemies from [[private military companies]].\n\nRaiden, who was inspired by the [[Sherlock Holmes]] stories and a fan's letter wanting a younger character to be featured in the series, originated from Hideo Kojima's desire to view Solid Snake from a different point of view. Raiden's inclusion in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' was kept secret from gamers before his debut; despite some players' reactions, the staff liked the character. To appeal to fans of the series who initially disliked Raiden, the character was redesigned for ''Metal Gear Solid 4''. He was again redesigned for both the cancelled game ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'' and its reboot ''Revengeance'' to portray a darker side of his character. In Japanese, the character is voiced by  [[Kenyu Horiuchi]] and in English by [[Quinton Flynn]].\n\nRaiden's debut role as the protagonist of ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' was controversial, however, due to his unexpected substitution for the established hero Solid Snake. Some critics defended the character, stating that fans were merely angered by the former's removal and that the latter was appealing. Despite this mixed reception, Raiden has been praised for his role and ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' redesign especially in his fight scene, and more for his role and design in ''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance'' where he was found as a better character than in previous installments.\n\n==Character design==\n===Initial concept===\n{{multiple image\n | footer    = Hideo Kojima created Raiden while Yoji Shinkawa designed him.\n | image1    = Hideo Kojima - Tokyo Game Show 2011 (1) (cropped).jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  =  \n | width1    = 170\n | image2    = Yoji Shinkawa.png\n | alt2      =\n | caption2  =\n | width2    = 150\n}}\nAccording to series creator [[Hideo Kojima]], the decision to make a new character to replace Solid Snake for most of ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' stemmed from the developer's desire to develop Snake from a third-person perspective. Kojima stated that Raiden's character and his perception by the audience were important to the overall feel of the story. The idea of having a second main character was inspired by the [[Sherlock Holmes]] short stories and novels in which the narrator is [[Dr. Watson]] rather than Holmes. Kojima said Snake was the game's protagonist rather than Raiden. Yoshikazu Matsuhana, assistant director for the project, was uncertain about this decision; he considered Raiden a \"weak-looking character\" but decided to follow Kojima.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Final Hours of Metal Gear Solid 2|website=[[GameSpot]]|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/btg_mgs2/p02_01.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103100148/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/btg_mgs2/p02_01.html|accessdate=July 3, 2011|archivedate=January 3, 2006}}</ref> The codename \"Raiden\" was based on that of the [[Mitsubishi J2M|Mitsubishi J2M Raiden]], a historical combat aircraft of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service]]. It was initially planned to be written in [[katakana]] as \"\u30e9\u30a4\u30c7\u30f3\", but was changed to the [[kanji]] form \"\u96f7\u96fb\" because of a resemblance to [[Osama bin Laden|Bin Laden]]'s \"Laden\" in katakana, \"\u30e9\u30fc\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://m.kotaku.com/5844190/what-osama-bin-laden-and-metal-gear-solid-have-in-common|title=What Osama bin Laden and Metal Gear Solid Have in Common|date=September 27, 2011|website=[[Kotaku]] |author=Ashcraft, Brian|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref> His full name was going to be \"Raiden Brannigan\" but the idea was scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709185620/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|title=MGS2 PRODUCTION BACKGROUND NOTES|publisher=Shinobu Webs|archivedate=July 9, 2013|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> The romantic relationship between Raiden and Rosemary was inspired by Kojima's experiences; their names, Jack and Rose, are a reference to characters in the film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref name=\"Making\"/> In ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', Raiden is considered to be a representation of the player through the experiences between the player and the character during the game.<ref name=Howell>\n{{cite web |author1=James Howell |author2=Ryan Payton |lastauthoramp=yes |title=The Kojima Productions Report Session 084 |publisher=[[Kojima Productions]] |date=March 20, 2008 |url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2008/03/000153.html |accessdate=November 24, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604144853/http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2008/03/000153.html |archivedate=2009-06-04 }}</ref>\n\nKojima received much fan mail; one letter from a girl stated she did not want to play a game with an old man. Kojima took this into consideration; he and his team designed Raiden to be more appealing to women.<ref name=\"volone\"/> Designer [[Yoji Shinkawa]] said he and the other character designers took much inspiration for Raiden's appearance from the ''[[bish\u014dnen]]'' archetype.<ref name=\"volone\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 3: Subsistence|year=2006|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Metal Gear Saga Vol. 1}}</ref> Because Raiden was a new character, the staff designed him carefully, giving him white hair to symbolize his introduction. Shinkawa also said Raiden had an overall feminine appearance.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite video game|title=The Document of Metal Gear Solid 2|year=2002|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Making of Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty}}</ref> His outfit\u2014the Skull Suit\u2014was difficult to  design until the staff decided on a \"bonelike\" concept. Shinkawa wanted to make Raiden sexually appealing, emphasizing the tightness of his clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp/gs/game/mgs2/art/third.html |title=Yoji Shinkawa Interview: Segment 3 |publisher=[[Konami]] |accessdate=March 1, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019131636/http://www.konami.jp/gs/game/mgs2/art/third.html |archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref> The design of Raiden's aqua-mask was inspired by ancient mystical [[ninjutsu]], where the ninja bites a scroll in the mouth during magic transformations. Raiden's final duel with the boss Solidus Snake was revised in the making of the game. Originally, to defeat Solidus, Raiden must cut off both his mechanical snake-like arms, then he must attack Solidus' back and sever the back bone vertebra connection, rendering Solidus no longer mobile. Following this, Raiden would finish Solidus by decapitating him similar to samurai fashion. The scene was rejected and instead Raiden would slice Solidus' stomach, another idea taken from samurais. However, this concept was also scrapped to simply Raiden slicing Solidus' vertebral column with the boss falling from the area to give the idea he could not accept his defeat.<ref name=\"production\">{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709185620/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|title=Metal Gear Solid 2 Production|archivedate=July 9, 2013|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Konami]] kept Raiden's starring role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' secret until the game's North American release; the company replaced Raiden with Snake in teaser trailers and other preview materials. Although Raiden appeared in several preview trailers in his scuba gear, his presence was not emphasized.<ref name=\"Making\" /> The surprise to fans that Raiden was not Snake was admitted by Kojima to have been inspired by the plot twist of ''[[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]]'' where the titular character played by [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was not a villain in that movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/commentary2.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713081833/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/commentary2.html|title=Big Shell Infiltration \uff5e Contact Peter Stillman|publisher=Shinobu Wbes|archivedate=July 13, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Raiden's appearance in the game was announced to the Japanese press on the day of the game's release in North America.<ref>{{cite video game|title=The Document of Metal Gear Solid 2|year=2002|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote=}}</ref> Due to negative response to Raiden's role in the game, Kojima said in retrospective that the team failed to properly show the character.<ref name=\"spong\"/>\n\n===Further development===\nRaiden's new design for ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' was a response to the criticism that only his face remained in his cybernetic body. Shinkawa was surprised by the way he illustrated Raiden. The staff noted that Raiden's debut in the game's trailer received notably positive responses; several video-game magazines promoted the game with Raiden's screenshots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mp.i-revo.jp/user.php/kp-ryan/entry/52.html |title=The KP Report Session 027 |publisher=mp.i.revo |work=Kojima Productions Report |author=Payton, Ryan |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703183506/http://mp.i-revo.jp/user.php/kp-ryan/entry/52.html |archivedate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Shinkawa stated Raiden was remade as a darker hero to appeal to the Western fanbase. Seeing [[Gray Fox (Metal Gear)|Gray Fox]] as one of his favorite characters, Shinkawa made Raiden be an archetype of such character, making Raiden a cyborg like him.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.3djuegos.com/comunidad-foros/tema/21118594/0/el-arte-de-metal-gear-el-legado-visual-de-yoji-shinkawa/|title=[- El Arte de Metal Gear {{!}} El legado visual de Yoji Shinkawa |publisher=3DJuegos |language=  fr |accessdate= November 26, 2018}}</ref> Kojima echoed similar comments, indicating he wanted to expand the character with another game.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://gamerant.com/hideo-kojima-solid-snake-project-ogre-metal-gear-rising-ts-123571/ |title= Hideo Kojima Talks Killing Snake, Project Ogre, Metal Gear Rising & More! |publisher= GameRant |author=Schirado, Tyler |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate= February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120325151051/http://gamerant.com/hideo-kojima-solid-snake-project-ogre-metal-gear-rising-ts-123571/ |archivedate= March 25, 2012}}</ref> In designing him, Shinkawa wanted to convey both Raiden's beauty and sorrow in his cybernetic body. He was given the ability to wield swords with his own legs, giving the players the impression he was a ninja.<ref>{{cite book |title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots Master Art Works |year=2009 |asin=B0033910T0 |publisher=Example Product Manufacturer |page=39}}</ref> Raiden's first fight against [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Vamp|Vamp]] in the game caused motion and voice actors difficulty because of carefully planned movements performed by the two fighters. The staff was satisfied with the outcome, considering it one of the best battles in the game.<ref name=\"solidfourmaking\">{{cite video|title=Making of Metal Gear Solid 4|medium=Blu-ray|publisher=Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH|date=2008}}</ref> Two actors were selected for the motion capture of Raiden; one did most of his appearances while another did his action sequences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp:80/mgs4/us/interview/02.html|title=Development|publisher=Konami|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427133319/http://www.konami.jp/mgs4/us/interview/02.html|archivedate=April 27, 2009|accessdate=September 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Raiden's fights in ''Guns of the Patriots'' were made to assist the weaker Solid Snake and appealed to previous fans of the series who disliked the character.<ref name=\"spong\">{{cite web|url=https://spong.com/feature/10110941/Interview-Hideo-Kojima-on-Metal-Gear-Rising/2|title=Interviews// Hideo Kojima on Metal Gear Rising|publisher=Spong|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128034922/https://spong.com/feature/10110941/Interview-Hideo-Kojima-on-Metal-Gear-Rising/2|archive-date=2018-11-28|url-status=live}}\n</ref> Because Raiden became a more active character in ''Guns of the Patriots'', Kojima expressed a desire in him returning in a future character as playable.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors\"/>\n\n[[File:Atsushi Inaba (cropped).jpg|thumb|Atsushi Inaba from Platinum Games oversaw Raiden's character in ''Rising'']]\nWhen ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'' was known as ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'', former producer Shigenobu Matsuyama hinted that Raiden's past as a child soldier would be elaborated upon and his weaknesses as a human would be explored. Matsuyama wanted Raiden to have as strong a role in the game as in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', leading him to become its main character.<ref name=\"eurogamer interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-13-metal-gear-solid-rising-interview?page=1 |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising Interview |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Wesley Yin-Poole |date=September 13, 2010 |accessdate=September 14, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917210657/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-13-metal-gear-solid-rising-interview?page=1 |archivedate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> Director [[Mineshi Kimura]] wanted Raiden to be able to move the way he did in the ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' trailers, wanting to show \"the stealth of the sword, and the strength of not even losing to the gun, and the fear and power you have with this blade\".<ref name=\"E32010 liveblog\" /> Matsuyama said they would focus on Raiden's strong will and physical strength so he would be enjoyable to control.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/pc/metal_gear_solid_rising/preview-2640.html |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising Preview |publisher=VideoGamer.com |author=Gatson, Martin |date=August 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003103501/http://www.videogamer.com/pc/metal_gear_solid_rising/preview-2640.html |archivedate=2012-10-03}}</ref> Raiden's design was changed during the game's development, leading to different promotional images of him.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://m.kotaku.com/5460065/metal-gear-solid-risings-raiden-has-changed |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising's Raiden Has Changed|website=[[Kotaku]] |author=McWhertor, Michael |date=January 29, 2010  |accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref> Following the game's reboot into a spin-off, developers stated that while Raiden \"has grown up\" in comparison to previous ''Metal Gear'' games, he is still conflicted with his life as a child soldier in the [[First Liberian Civil War]], leading him to become a \"dark hero\".<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edge-online.com/news/e3-2012-platinum-details-metal-gear-rising-revengeance |title=E3 2012: Platinum details Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance |publisher=Edge |date=June 1, 2012 |accessdate=June 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604012444/http://www.edge-online.com/news/e3-2012-platinum-details-metal-gear-rising-revengeance |archivedate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Shinkawa designed Raiden's new body to emphasize his dark heroism, contrasting with his ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' persona. Shimkawa later discussed with Platinum Games' Kenji Saito about including his quasi-human look. Raiden's loss of an eye also represents his transformation across the story while also comparing him with the previous antagonist [[Solidus Snake]]. Tamari also explained that the cybernetic functions Raiden has was based on research led by the [[University of Texas]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance The Complete Official Guide|publisher=Piggyback |year=2013|isbn=978-0307897169}}</ref> In response to complaints that ''Rising'' appeared to contradict Raiden's ending in ''Guns of the Patriots'', the Kojima Productions staff said the game would explain what happened with Raiden's life.<ref name=\"session153\">{{cite web|title=Kojima Productions Podcast Session 153 |publisher=Kojima Productions |date=January 26, 2012 |url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2012/01/ |accessdate=December 29, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407190933/http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2012/01/ |archivedate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> While Steven Armstrong was the game's final antagonist, the character of Jetstream Sam was developed to be Raiden's rival, something Shinkawa and fellow designer Kenichirou Yoshimura worked together to make both of them contrast each other through their visual appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://platinumgames.com/2012/12/27/staying-true-to-metal-gear/|title=Statying True to Metal Gear|website=Platinum Games |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231161729/http://platinumgames.com/2012/12/27/staying-true-to-metal-gear/ |archivedate=December 31, 2012 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe team in charge of ''Revengeance'' depicted Raiden as a more mature character than in his previous appearances; they said his swordplay is not based on any samurai and that Raiden's cybernetic body includes heels because they \"are very uncomfortable to run in or fight in&nbsp;... and besides he's a guy!\".<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2012/06/11/metal-gear-rising-preview-and-interview-platinum-medal-463731/|title=Metal Gear Rising preview and interview \u2013 Platinum medal|publisher=Metro|date=June 11, 2012|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128034925/https://metro.co.uk/2012/06/11/metal-gear-rising-preview-and-interview-platinum-medal-463731/|archive-date=2018-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref> When developing the game's, the team thought of Raiden's revenge against his enemies, which resulted in the title \"Reveangeance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-story-of-the-chemical-reaction-that-gave-metal-gear-rising-its-revengeance|title=The story of the 'chemical reaction' that gave Metal Gear Rising its Revengeance|newspaper=Financial Post|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Writer Etsu Tamari expressed joy in the final product and expected that in the future, the team could make another game focused on Raiden.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/3/6/4070250/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-writer-on-future-dlc-and-how-the-story|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance writer on future DLC and how the story got shifted years into the future|website=Polygon|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210063241/https://www.polygon.com/2013/3/6/4070250/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-writer-on-future-dlc-and-how-the-story|archive-date=2018-12-10|url-status=live}}\n</ref> In a further analysis of how to write Raiden in ''Revengeance'', Tamari stated he needed a new character that would bring him support in the form of the dog-like robot named Bladewolf; Similar to how Snake guides Raiden in ''Sons of Liberty'', the mature Raiden acts like a mentor to Bladewolf across the story resulting in his character arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/noticias/dos-dlc-metal-gear-rising-seran-precuelas-49082|title=Dos DLC de Metal Gear Rising ser\u00e1n precuelas|date=6 March 2013|publisher=Hobby Consolas|language=Spanish|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Writer Etsu Tamari wanted to portray Raiden as a more mature person who wishes to take Snake's footsteps.<ref name=\"gamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamer.ne.jp/news/201209270035/|website=Gamer|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 5, 2020|title=\u3010TGS 2012\u3011\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u306b\u96f7\u96fb\u5f79\u306e\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u3092\u8fce\u3048\u3001\u300c\u65ac\u308b\u300d\u6c17\u6301\u3061\u826f\u3055\u304b\u3089\u96f7\u96fb\u306e\u5fc3\u306e\u845b\u85e4\u306a\u3069\u3001\u5236\u4f5c\u79d8\u8a71\u3082\u8a9e\u3089\u308c\u305f\u300c\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300d\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u30ec\u30dd}}</ref> [[Atsushi Inaba]] wanted the gameplay of ''Revengeance'' fit Raiden's style of characterization, resulting in the use of parries rather than defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/77006/how-stealth-came-back-into-metal-gear-rising-revengeance|title=How stealth came back into Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|publisher=Shack News|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Inaba felt honored to work in ''Revengeance'' due to how he was able to see a more mature version of the character to the point of wishing for a sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/why-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-has-parrying-and-other-questions-for-platinumgames/|title=Why Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance Has Parrying And Other Qs For PlatinumGames\n|date=11 December 2012\n|publisher=Silicoenra|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> \n\nRaiden is first depicted as a white-haired adult who uses a protective suit known as a {{nihongo|\"Skull Suit\"|\u30b9\u30ab\u30eb\u30b9\u30fc\u30c4|Sukaru S\u016btsu}} for his missions.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' Your new Sneaking suit uses electrofiber technology, a by-product of fiber-optics research. The texture isn't far removed from rubber but the material protects against a wide range of toxic substances. The suit itself has a wide array of built-in sensors. It is referred to as \"Smart Skin\" in military R&D. Data about damage to different regions of the body, including blood loss, is exchanged between the suit and the intravenous nanomachines to create a bio-feedback system. ... They call this the \"Skull Suit\" in FOXHOUND.}}</ref> In ''Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots'' Raiden's entire body below the upper jaw is replaced with a prototype cybernetic body; his blood is replaced with a military substitute called {{nihongo|\"White Blood\"|\u767d\u8840|Shiro Chi}} that requires regular maintenance.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Naomi Hunter:''' That's right. Raiden's blood is an older type of artificial blood that was used by the military ... Called white blood. After it's been in use for a while, the blood needs to be dialyzed ... Filtered. Right now, he's slipping into autotoxemia.}}</ref> His original cybernetic body is replaced with a black one that also covers the left eye for ''Revengeance''.  Although proficient at all types of weaponry, Raiden specializes in wielding swords that resonate at high frequencies for the last fights in ''Sons of Liberty'',<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Olga asked me to give it to you. Besides, I'm not a big fan of blades.}}</ref> and during ''Guns of the Patriots'' and ''Revengeance''. {{Clear}}\n\n===Personality and portrayal===\n[[File:Quinton Flynn.jpg|thumb|upright|Quinton Flynn has enjoyed doing the English voice for Raiden.]]\n\nIn his first appearances Raiden is a rookie agent who is inexperienced as a result of training only in [[virtual reality]]. He later reveals, however, that he was a child soldier known as {{nihongo|\"[[Jack the Ripper]]\"|\u30b8\u30e3\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30ea\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc|Jakku Za Ripp\u0101}} who killed several enemies in a civil war and is ashamed of his past.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' No, it was field training, when I was a kid. I lied, Snake. I have more field experience than I can remember. It's not VR that's doing this to me. / '''Solid Snake:''' Raiden, we don't carry guns to take people down. We're not here to help some politician either. / '''Raiden:''' You can say that because you're a legend, a hero. I'm Jack the Ripper, a dirty reminder -- of a terrible mistake.}}</ref> This affects Raiden's personality; he begins to believe he is only useful in the battlefield and his relationship with his girlfriend [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Rosemary|Rosemary]] would not work.<ref name=\"war\"/><ref name=\"past\"/> Manipulation by the Patriots causes him to believe he has no free will. [[Solid Snake]] encourages Raiden to ignore what people tell him and to become self-reliant when problem-solving.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Listen, don't obsess over words so much. Find the meaning behind the words, then decide. You can find your own name. And your own future&nbsp;... I know you didn't have much in terms of choices this time. But everything you felt, thought about during this mission is yours. And what you decide to do with them is your choice ... / '''Raiden:''' You mean start over? / '''Solid Snake:''' Yeah, a clean slate. A new name, new memories. Choose your own legacy. It's for you to decide. It's up to you}}</ref> His original personality was that of a \"creep or a weirdo\", who licked bird doodoo but this was discarded by the staff.<ref name=\"production\"/>\n\nIn the Japanese versions of the games, Raiden has been voiced by [[Kenyu Horiuchi]],<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:\u5800\u5185 \u8ce2\u96c4 |publisher=Kenyu Office |language=Japanese |url=http://www.kenyu-office.com/profile/horiuchikenyu.html |accessdate=October 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928204054/http://www.kenyu-office.com/profile/horiuchikenyu.html |archivedate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> who first saw him as an attractive young man whose actions in ''Son of Liberty'' were challenging for his identity. Horiuchi was impressed by the characterization shown across the game, believing him to fit with other members featured in the game. Kojima liked Horiuchi's work, believing Raiden became popular in Japan in part because of his performance, something which he felt the character lacked in Western regions.<ref name=\"gamer\"/> could understand the character's pain; despite becoming a cyborg, Raiden still acts like a human.<ref name=\"solidfourmaking\"/> Horiuchi took a liking to Raiden's spin-off game, ''Revengeance'', as he acted as the lead for the first time but was still glad that he got meet new actors who appeared in the game, most notably the actor behind Doktor. THe actors also liked the inclusion of Raiden's sidekick, LQ-84i (later renamed Bladewolf), as they believe that ninjas like Raiden obligatory need dogs as allies. Another relationship the actors liked was Raiden's exchanges with Courtney due to few female characters being present in the game but felt they made the characters get along properly.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors\">{{cite web|url=https://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/538/538783/|title=\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u304c\u767b\u5834\uff01 \u6570\u3005\u306e\u5236\u4f5c\u79d8\u8a71\u304c\u660e\u304b\u3055\u308c\u305f\u300e\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300f\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8|website=Dengeki Online|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Horiuchi felt confident in being in doing Raiden's voice as the lead, believing his thirty years of experience made him suitable for the role.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/201209/24021722.html|title=\u96f7\u96fb\u73fe\u308b\uff01\u3000\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u3092\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u306b\u8fce\u3048\u305f\u300e\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300f\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u3010TGS2012\u3011|website=Famitsu|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCasting director Kris Zimmerman chose [[Quinton Flynn]], with whom she had previously worked, to voice Raiden in the series' English adaptation. Flynn remembers having a long time to develop the character and being instructed by Zimmerman to use an older voice from a character he previously voiced. Flynn said Raiden was one of his favorite video-game voice characters and noted a difference between his roles in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' and ''Metal Gear Solid 4'';<ref name=\"gamingliberty\">{{cite web |title=Raiden Speaks! An interview with Quinton Flynn |publisher=The Gaming Liberty |date=May 21, 2011 |url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/05/21/raiden-speaks-an-interview-with-quinton-flynn-part-1/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625005316/http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/05/21/raiden-speaks-an-interview-with-quinton-flynn-part-1 |archivedate=June 25, 2011}}</ref> Flynn was pleased with working alongside [[David Hayter]] whom he often interacted while recording the game.<ref name=\"metalgearinfor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metalgearinformer.com/?p=19735|title=QUINTON FLYNN (RAIDEN): THE KOJIMA \u2013 KONAMI SPLIT IS UNFORTUNATE, BUT THE METAL GEAR SERIES SHOULD CONTINUE REGARDLESS|website=Metal Gear Informer|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The English voice recording was overlooked by Scott Dolph, who reported back saying the English voice for Raiden was more neutral than the original Japanese voice.<ref name=\"production\"/> For ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' Flynn used a deeper voice to match the cyborg Raiden in contrast to the original, youthful Raiden of ''Metal Gear Solid 2''. Flynn said the voice he used was \"grizzled, yeah\u2014but different enough from the style of Snake\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/06/20/mgs4s-raiden-speaks|title=MGS4's Raiden Speakes|date=June 18, 2008|website=IGN|accessdate=August 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816195559/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/06/20/mgs4s-raiden-speaks|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref> During development of ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'', Flynn was not informed about the work despite Raiden being in the trailer. As a result, Flynn kept low hopes in regards to the idea of being cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2011/05/23/raiden-voice-actor-in-the-dark-regarding-mgs-rising.aspx|title=Raiden Voice Actor \"In The Dark\" Regarding MGS: Rising|website=Game Informer|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Addressing ''Guns of the Patriots''{{'}}s Raiden as more agressive than the original one, Flynn stated his favorite take on the character was ''Revengeance''{{'}}s as it there he acted as a \"blend\" between the two incarnations. He felt honored for taking the role of Raiden again, having received a \"Behind The Voice Actors\" award for his work.<ref name=\"metalgearinfor\"/> In 2015, Flynn stated he was pleased with Raiden's role in ''Reveangence'' and that he would have liked a new sequel Raiden as the lead. Internal problems between Kojima Productions and Konami, however, left Flynn worried there might not be another game in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gamingbolt.com/konami-were-considering-metal-gear-rising-2-kojima-break-up-unfortunate-raidens-va|title=Konami Were Considering Metal Gear Rising 2, Kojima Break Up Unfortunate: Raiden's VA|publisher=Gaming Bolt|accessdate=December 3, 2018|author=Sinha, Ravi|date=May 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204102018/https://gamingbolt.com/konami-were-considering-metal-gear-rising-2-kojima-break-up-unfortunate-raidens-va|archive-date=2018-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKojima Productions compared the experiences and ways of thinking of Raiden and Solid Snake. During the game's climax, Raiden stays handcuffed until his final fight against [[Solidus Snake]]; Snake escapes from his handcuffs to follow [[Revolver Ocelot]], emphasizing Raiden's lack of freedom. Hideo Kojima compared Raiden and Snake with [[movie monsters]] [[King Kong]] and [[Godzilla]], respectively; the former was taken from his home and his nature changes upon meeting Rosemary, whereas the latter will continue fighting against mankind's menaces. Defeating Solidus, Snake encourages Raiden to trust himself and believe in his own choices. This is further addressed by the staff's motivation to make a new sequel to ''Metal Gear'' without Kojima.<ref name=\"Making\" /> Kojima also likened Raiden with [[John Rambo]] from the ''[[Rambo (film series)|Rambo]]'' series because both characters always find themselves taking part in battles despite their desire for a peaceful resolution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CVG_News/status/304968402521423872 |title=CVG News |publisher=Twitter |work=Computer and Video Games |date=February 22, 2013 |accessdate=March 3, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623151620/https://twitter.com/CVG_News/status/304968402521423872 |archivedate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> Raiden himself believes that he is destined to fight based on his upbringing during ''Revengeance'' while also following the concept of ''[[katsujinken]]'' in which samurai kill in order to protect the weak.<ref name=\"growth\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n{{multiple image\n | footer    = Raiden was designed as a cyborg in ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' (left) while in ''Rising'' his new appearance (right) was meant to emphasize his darker characterization.\n | image1    = MetalGearSolid4Raiden.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  =\n | width1    = 150\n | image2    = RaidenRevengeance.png\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  =\n | width2    = 240\n}}\n===Main games===\n''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' introduces the player to Raiden in the Plant chapter; Jack is introduced as a newly recruited, virtual reality-trained member of [[FOXHOUND]] with no live-combat experience before his current mission.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' Just a precaution. You are now designated \"Raiden.\" All right, Raiden. You've already covered infiltration in VR Training. / '''Raiden:''' I've completed three hundred missions in VR. I feel like some kind of legendary mercenary ...}}</ref> He is assisted via [[Receiver (radio)|Codec]] by his commanding officer the Colonel and his girlfriend Rosemary. Raiden's initial objective is to rescue several hostages from a terrorist group known as the Sons of Liberty.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' Jack, I'm a part of this mission. / '''Raiden:''' Colonel, what the hell is going on? / '''Colonel:''' Raiden, meet the mission analyst. She'll be overseeing the data saving and support.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' You have two missions objectives. One: infiltrate the offshore decontamination facility \"Big Shell\" and safeguard the President and other hostages. And two: disarm the terrorists by any means necessary.}}</ref> During his mission, Raiden is helped by mercenary [[Solid Snake]] and spy [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Olga Gurlukovich|Olga Gurlukovich]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Olga:''' I was sent to provide you support. / '''Raiden:''' Support? Who sent you? The Colonel? / '''Olga:''' No ... the Patriots. ...My child is ... being held hostage by the Patriots.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Are you two really an NGO? / '''Otacon:''' Insofar as we're a nonprofit organization of civilians advocating a cause, yes. The cause happens to be the eradication of Metal Gear. / '''Solid Snake:''' We work on our own. But it's a cause worth fighting for.}}</ref>\n\nAs the story progresses, Jack is revealed to be a former child soldier who fought for the Sons of Liberty leader [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Solidus Snake|Solidus Snake]] during the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref name=\"war\"/><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solidus Snake:''' The eighties&nbsp;... the civil war. You were one of the best among the child soldiers that fought in that conflict. When you were barely ten years old, you became the leader of the small boys unit&nbsp;... I was your godfather, I named you.}}</ref> After the war's end, Raiden was given a normal life and tried to forget his past.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' When the civil war ended, those of us who survived were taken in by NGO's. They gave me a new life in the States. I can't complain. But nothing's changed&nbsp;... What I hate more than anything else in the world is my own past.}}</ref> It is revealed that a clandestine organization known as [[The Patriots (Metal Gear)|The Patriots]] is controlling his actions and his commanding officer is revealed as their computer-generated [[Artificial intelligence]] (AI).<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Otacon:''' I think it means&nbsp;... you've been talking to an AI. / '''Raiden:''' That's impossible! / '''Otacon:''' The Colonel probably isn't GW per se. GW was most likely stimulating cortical activity in the dormant part of your brain through signal manipulation of your own nanomachines. The Colonel is in part your own creation, cobbled together from expectations and experience&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Emma''': GW is a system that allows the Patriots to decide what will be recorded in tomorrow's history.}}</ref> One of their spies becomes Raiden's girlfriend and the two fall in love.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' No, it's something else. That day at Federal Hall two years ago&mdash;it wasn't a coincidence. I was ordered to keep an eye on you&nbsp;... / '''Raiden:''' Keep an eye on me? / '''Rosemary:''' Yes&mdash;by the Patriots. / '''Raiden:''' You're a spy;&nbsp;... / '''Rosemary:''' Jack, I thought I was acting, because that was my job. But I did fall in love with you, that wasn't an act.}}</ref> Raiden defeats Solidus after the Patriots' AIs tell him his death would also trigger those of Olga's child and Rosemary, the latter of whom is revealed to have been pregnant with Raiden's child during the mission.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel''': It's time for the final exercise. Raiden, take Solidus down. / '''Raiden''': Think again! I'm through doing what I'm told! / '''Colonel''': Oh really? Aren't you forgetting something? \"If you die, my child dies.\" The termination of vital signals from your nanomachines means the death of Olga's child. Not to mention the death of Rose. She's wired the same way. / '''Raiden''': Rose -- does she actually exist? / '''Colonel''': (Using Rosemary's voice) Of course I do, Jack! You have to believe me! / '''Raiden''': Damn&nbsp;... / '''Colonel''': It will be a fight to the death.}}</ref> He later reunites with Rosemary, and both decide to stay together to raise their unborn child.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Of course. This is where we first met ... I remember now -- Today is the day I met you. That's it. I think I found something to pass along to the future. He said all living things want their genes to live on. / '''Rosemary:''' Are you talking about the baby? / '''Raiden:''' Yeah. But genes aren't the only thing you pass on. There are too many things that aren't written into our DNA. It's up to us to teach that to our children.}}</ref>\n\n''[[Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots]]'' (set five years after ''Metal Gear Solid 2'') features Raiden after rescuing Olga's daughter [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Sunny|Sunny]] from the Patriots,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Jack's gone? I used to work with the guy. He saved Sunny from the Patriots. / '''Roy Campbell:''' He disappeared soon after that.}}</ref> and searching the corpse of the mercenary [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]] for [[EVA (Metal Gear)|Big Mama]] in exchange.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Snake:''' Raiden, where have you been all this time? What have you been doing? Finding what? / '''Raiden:''' The corpse of Big Boss. / '''Snake:''' What? / '''Raiden:''' I was asked to do this in exchange for Sunny's location. / '''Snake:''' Matka Pluku ... Big Mama.}}</ref> The trauma of his breakup with Rosemary and the apparent miscarriage of his child have made Raiden believe he belongs on the battlefield.<ref name=\"war\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' After the Big Shell Incident, he became unstable. Memories began to resurface from his childhood, when he fought for Solidus in the Liberian Civil War. And in the midst of all that ... The baby we had together&nbsp;... It hadn't even been born yet. Jack slowly stopped coming home. And when he did, he'd be dead drunk, sometimes covered in cuts and bruises.}}</ref><ref name=\"past\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' I've got nothing to lose. / '''Snake:''' Don't be an idiot. You know you've got someone to protect. / '''Raiden:''' It was never going to work out for me. It even \"rained\" the day I was born.}}</ref> Raiden is fitted with a cybernetic [[exoskeleton]] as a result of the Patriots' machinations;<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4 Database|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Raiden}}</ref> he helps Solid Snake in the fight against [[Revolver Ocelot|Liquid Ocelot]], wanting to obtain the Patriots' powers. After several encounters with Liquid's men, Raiden stays in the ship ''Outer Haven'' to protect Snake as he shuts down the Patriots' AIs.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Snake:''' It's my duty to put an end to all of this. / '''Raiden:''' All right. I'll make sure they don't get through. / '''Otacon:''' Stay with me, Snake. Hold on until we insert the virus.}}</ref> In an epilogue, Rosemary tells Raiden their child was not miscarried; her marriage to [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Roy Campbell|Roy Campbell]] was a hoax to protect her and their son from the Patriots. Upon hearing this news, Raiden reconciles with Rosemary.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' You said miscarriage&nbsp;... / '''Rosemary:''' I lied. I had a healthy baby boy. Roy pretended to by my husband&nbsp;... To protect me&nbsp;... And our son. Only until you'd completed your mission. To shield us from Patriot eyes&nbsp;... / '''Raiden:''' I'll never leave you alone again. Like a scene from Beauty and the Beast. / '''Rosemary:''' Don't say that. You're no beast. You're my husband. And his father. And me&nbsp;... I'm going to do my very best&nbsp;... to be the wife and mother this family deserves.}}</ref>\n\nRaiden returns as the main character in ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'', which is set four years after ''Metal Gear Solid 4''.<ref name=\"E32010 liveblog\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5565341/konami-e3-liveblog-is-right-here-hopefully-with-lightning-and-whips |title=Konami E3 Liveblog Is Right Here, Hopefully With Lightning And Whips |website=[[Kotaku]] |author=Stephen Totilo |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=June 16, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619063911/http://kotaku.com/5565341/konami-e3-liveblog-is-right-here-hopefully-with-lightning-and-whips |archivedate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> He is a member of the [[private military company]] (PMC) Maverick Security in multiple tasks while raising money for his family. They are attacked by a group of terrorists called Desperado Enforcement LLC that kill his protectee, N'ani, and leave Raiden near to death with mercenary Jeatstream Sam taking a liking to his fighting style.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Sam:''' Now I see. You deny your weapon its purpose! It yearns to bath in the blood of your enemies... but you hold it back! / '''Raiden:''' No... My sword is a tool of justice.}}</ref> He is saved by the elder scientist Wilhelm \"Doktor\" Voight and starts working with them to fight Desperado.<ref name=\"g4tv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/58828/official-e3-preview-of-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/ |title=Official E3 Preview of Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance |publisher=G4TV |date=June 4, 2012 |accessdate=August 29, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310115904/http://www.g4tv.com/videos/58828/official-e3-preview-of-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/ |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> Raiden fights Desperado's LQ-84i, an AI placed in a robot who works for Desperado but Raiden takes pity on it and has Doktor restore it under the name of Bladewolf who assists him.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Kevin:''' You sure you want the K-9000 there along for this one? / '''Raiden:''' I had the good Doktor make some adjustments along with the repairs. Remote wiping and AI wiping have been disabled. So yeah, so I say let's throw him a bone.}}</ref> Raiden's vengeful obsession with Desperado becomes personal when he discovers during a mission to Mexico that Desperado and World Marshal Inc have kidnapped several children, surgically removed their brains to place into cybernetic bodies, and were planning to subject them to VR training modeled on his own.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:'''Are they making these kids into cyborgs?}}</ref> Raiden then resigns from Maverick to pursue and retrieve the children's [[brain case]]s from World Marshal in Colorado, embracing his sadistic persona \"Jack the Ripper\" due to his constant struggles with Sam and Desperado's cyborg Moonsoon.<ref name=\"growth\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' You're right&nbsp;... about me, I mean. I knew something was&nbsp;... off. After the Patriots, I thought I could walk off the battlefield and into a normal life&nbsp;... but here I am, surrounded by death, arguing philosophy with terrorists. I told myself this was about justice, about protecting the weak&nbsp;... but I was wrong. / '''Monsoon:''' Then you admit it? / '''Raiden:''' I learned young that killing your enemies felt good. Really good. In America, my friends, my family&nbsp;... they helped me forget the devil inside&nbsp;... but who am I kidding? I was born to kill! The bit about my sword, that \"means of justice\" stuff? I guess I just needed something to keep \"the Ripper\" in check when I was knee-deep in bodies ... / '''Monsoon:''' You ... / '''Raiden:''' But you..all this ... is a wake-up call to what I really believe ... what I really am. / '''Monsoon:''' What are you saying / '''Raiden:''' I'm saying Jack is back!}}</ref> Raiden defeats Desperado and learns that Steven Armstrong was using PMCs to distract him as he attempts to create a new [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' I've taken Marshal HQ. / '''Boris:''' Raiden, what Sundowner said.  / '''Raiden:''' I know. Anything that'll rival 9-11 cannot be good... and in three hours}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Armstong:''' Trust me, a little war can work wonder. / '''Raiden:''' So grease the gears with some innocent blood, is that it? / '''Armstrong:''' Relax Jack. It's a war on terror. We're not to kill out civilians.}}</ref> When Bladewolf passes Raiden's the word of the late Sam, Raiden stops Armstrong's actions and decides not to return to Maverick and travels to the [[Middle East]] to battle World Marshal mercenaries.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Armstrong! I said my sword was a tool of justice. Not used in anger. Not used for vengeance. But now... Now I'm not so sure. And besides, this isn't my sword.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Sorry Boris. / '''Boris:''' I understand, but then ... what will you do? / '''Raiden:''' I've got my own war to fight.}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances ===\nRaiden does not appear in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater]]'' but he is parodied throughout the game by debuting character Raikov.<ref name=\"raikov\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.1up.com/features/saving-private-raiden?pager.offset=3|title=Saving Private Raiden|website=[[1UP.com]]|accessdate=June 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130116083043/http://www2.1up.com/features/saving-private-raiden?pager.offset=3|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> Raiden appears in a series of comical scenes in an early promotional trailer for ''Guns of the Patriots'', in which he fights for control of the franchise with Solid Snake. A sequel to the trailer titled \"Metal Gear Raiden: Snake Eraser\" was produced; Raiden travels to the past to assassinate [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]] but fails comically.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/metalgearsolid4/news/6133819/tgs-2005-metal-gear-raiden-snake-eraser?mode=news|title=TGS 2005: Metal Gear Raiden: Snake Eraser|website=[[GameSpot]] |author=Niizumi, Hirohiko |date=September 18, 2005 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> In the trailer's English version, Raiden is voiced by [[Charlie Schlatter]] (the voice actor for Raikov) rather than Quinton Flynn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Charlie-Schlatter/|title=Charlie Schlatter|publisher=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Raiden's ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' version appears in the ''[[Metal Gear Solid: Portable Ops#Portable Ops Plus|Metal Gear Solid: Portable Ops Plus]]'' expansion pack as an unlockable character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/mgs-portable-ops-dated-nov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060438/http://www.1up.com/news/mgs-portable-ops-dated-nov|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 21, 2013|title=MGS: Portable Ops Plus Dated Nov. 13 for US|website=[[1UP.com]]|author=Pigna, Kris|date=October 17, 2007|accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref> His ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' incarnation appears as a playable character in ''[[Metal Gear Online]]''.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/metal-gear-online-adds-raiden|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019184939/http://www.1up.com/news/metal-gear-online-adds-raiden|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|title=Metal Gear Online adds Raiden, Vamp|website=[[1UP.com]]|author=Gifford, Kevin|date=February 18, 2009|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes]]'', Raiden stars in a non-canonical mission titled \"Jamais Vu\". Having time-travelled to the past,<ref>''Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes'' Jamais Vu trailer, Kojima Productions (2013).<br />'''Kazuhira Miller:''' But we've [MSF] got a secret weapon. A man [Raiden] from another world. A dark and distant future. A man turned into a war-machine with no human body for those bastards [body-snatchers] to snatch.</ref> he infiltrates Camp Omega under orders from [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Militaires Sans Frontieres|MSF]]. His aim is to incapacitate a group of soldiers known as the \"body snatchers\", a reference to the android replicators in Kojima's video game ''[[Snatcher (video game)|Snatcher]]''. His appearance in this game is modeled on that in ''Metal Gear Rising''.\n\nThe ''Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty'' 2007 [[comic book]] adaptation by Alex Garner retells Raiden's story with few changes. His relationship with Solidus is explored when he remembers his past; when Solidus about to kill him, Raiden is saved by Snake.<ref>{{cite book|title=Metal Gear Solid: Sons Of Liberty Volume 2|publisher=IDW Publishing |date=December 25, 2007|isbn=978-1-60010-111-3 |author1=Garner, Alex |author2=Wood, Ashley }}</ref> The game's novelization by [[Raymond Benson]] makes minor modifications to Raiden's history, except for the moment he receives Olga's sword, resulting in a change to his battle psyche. When Raiden kills Solidus he cuts the rope on [[Federal Hall National Memorial]]'s flagpole, causing an American flag to cover his enemy's body. This scene was deleted from the original game due to the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Metal Gear Solid 2: The Novel: Sons of Liberty |publisher=Del Rey |date=November 24, 2009 |isbn=978-0-345-50343-5 |author=Benson, Raymond |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/metalgearsolid200bens }}</ref>\n\nOutside the ''Metal Gear'' series, Raiden appears in the video game ''[[LittleBigPlanet (PlayStation 3)|LittleBigPlanet]]'' as a sticker and a playable sack-boy character in the ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' [[downloadable content]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/littlebigplanet/news/6202572/little-big-planet-update-metal-gear-solid-4-pack-impressions?sid=6202572&mode=previews|title=Little Big Planet Update: Metal Gear Solid 4 Pack Impressions|website=[[GameSpot]] |date=December 19, 2008|author=Torres, Ricardo |accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> He is an unlockable character in ''[[Evolution Skateboarding]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/sports/evolutionskateboarding/cheats.html?tag=tabs%253Bcheats|title=Evolution Skateboarding Hints & Cheats|website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> He also appears in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' as a collectible sticker and in ''[[Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood]]'' as an alternative skin for [[Ezio Auditore da Firenze]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/17/assassins-creed-brotherhood-play-as-raiden|title=Unlock Raiden in Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood|website=[[IGN]] |author=Ivan, Tom|date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Raiden is playable in the video games ''[[PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale]]'' and ''[[Super Bomberman R]]'' using his ''Metal Gear Rising'' design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-07-30-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-leak-outs-characters-stages |title=PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale leak outs characters, stages |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Phillips, Tom |date=July 30, 2012 |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801210326/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-07-30-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-leak-outs-characters-stages |archivedate=August 1, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vidaextra.com/accion/solid-snake-raiden-xavier-woods-muchos-personajes-se-unen-super-bomberman-r-su-nueva-actualizacion|title=Solid Snake, Raiden, Xavier Woods y muchos m\u00e1s personajes se unen a Super Bomberman R con su nueva actualizaci\u00f3n|date=27 June 2018|publisher=Vida Extra|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref> The [[webseries]] ''[[Mega64]]'' includes a parody of Raiden's story in ''Revengeance''; the character struggles against his darker persona while making breakfast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.platinumgames.com/games/metal-gear-rising-revengeance?age-verified=a08f2a98aa|title=History|publisher=Platinum Games|accessdate=December 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214070700/https://www.platinumgames.com/games/metal-gear-rising-revengeance?age-verified=a08f2a98aa|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Quote box |width = 26em |align = right |quote = \"Raiden was one of the most hated characters in gaming, mostly because he abruptly replaced Snake as the lead in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', though it didnt help that he was prone to fits of whining. Even though he showed flashes of swordsmanship akin to the beloved Cyborg Ninja, fans rejected him with a passion. Perhaps thats why ''MGS'' creator Hideo Kojima decided to try and reform Raiden in the fans eyes, by going all the way with his Cyborg Ninja tribute. When Raiden burst back onto the stage in ''Metal Gear Solid 4'', he had transitioned into an unbeatable cyborg ninja. His unplayable appearances in ''MGS4'' won him so many new fans, he earned his rightful place as the star of his own game, ''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance''.\" |source = \u2014 GamesRadar <ref name=gr/>}}\n===Critical reaction===\nRaiden's replacement of fan favorite Solid Snake in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' proved controversial; [[GamesRadar]] considered the replacement a reason to dislike the series.<ref name=Radd>{{cite web|title='Controversial' Games: Dealing with Fan Backlash |date=November 10, 2009 |author=David Radd |publisher=Industry Gamers |url=http://www.industrygamers.com/galleries/controversial-games-dealing-with-fan-backlash/6/ |accessdate=2009-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118011716/http://www.industrygamers.com/galleries/controversial-games-dealing-with-fan-backlash/6 |archivedate=November 18, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=5 reasons to hate Metal Gear Solid |date=November 10, 2009|author=Reparaz, Mikel|publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/5-reasons-to-hate-metal-gear-solid/a-201104251739927009/g-20100610112655981027|accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> The same site criticized Raiden's role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' several times and called his inclusion one of the worst aspects of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shit characters who almost ruined their great games|author=Meikleham, Dave|publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/shit-characters-who-almost-ruined-their-great-games/a-20100325125657826031/g-2005120719070989166259|accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gaming's most bizarre decisions |date=December 10, 2009 |author=Meikleham, Dave |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/gamings-most-bizarre-decisions/a-2009121013514764096/g-2005120719070989166259/p-3 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322130140/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/gamings-most-bizarre-decisions/a-2009121013514764096/g-2005120719070989166259/p-3/ |archivedate=March 22, 2016 }}</ref> Snake's voice actor, [[David Hayter]], was also surprised by the inclusion of Raiden in ''Sons of Liberty'' believing his character was meant to be returning protagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalgearinformer.com/?p=13843|title=DAVID HAYTER ON HIS ROLE AS SNAKE: 'I TRIED TO DO SOMETHING VERY SPECIFIC WITH THIS CHARACTER'|website=Metal Gear Informer|date=6 April 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> In 2004, ''GameAxis Unwired'' published a fake interview in which Hideo Kojima expressed regret for creating the character.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Santos, Shoeless Wayne|date=September 2004|url=https://books.google.com/?id=G-kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT2&dq=The+News+That+Never+Was+GameAxis+Unwired+Raiden#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The News That Never Was|journal=GameAxis Unwired|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|issn=0219-872X|issue=|page=4|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> While calling ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' one of the biggest disappointments in video-game history, [[UGO Networks]]' Marissa Meli cited Raiden's debut as a key problem with the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trolled: The Biggest Disappointments in Video Games |publisher=UGO Networks |date=June 3, 2011 |author=Meli, Marissa |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/metal-gear-solid-2-2 |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611072134/http://www.ugo.com/games/metal-gear-solid-2-2 |archivedate=June 11, 2011 }}</ref> The book ''Playing with Videogames'' states that Raiden's inclusion was intended to surprise ''Metal Gear'' fans who, instead of playing as Snake, played as his opposite. Writer James Newman commented that fans' reactions were highly negative; they acted as though Kojima had betrayed their expectations. He compared Raiden to the controversial ''[[Star Wars]]'' character [[Jar Jar Binks]]. Newman considered trailers for ''Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater'' in which Raiden is mocked to be Konami's comic response to fans' disapproval.<ref name=\"playingwithvideogames\">{{cite book |title=Playing with Videogames |pages=39\u201340 |last=Newman |first=James |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-415-38523-7}}</ref> \n[[Eurogamer]]'s Tom Bramwell enjoyed Raiden's role, commenting that his interactions with the other characters also helped expand Solid Snake's character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 2 : Sons of Liberty - Review |website=Eurogamer |date=December 3, 2002 |author=Bramwell, Tom |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_mgs2_ps2 |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826060156/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_mgs2_ps2 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> Raiden's introduction was given an award for \"Biggest Surprise\" by [[GameSpot]] in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|title=Biggest Surprise |website=GameSpot |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/bestof_2001/p2_09.html |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008063452/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/bestof_2001/p2_09.html |archivedate=October 8, 2013 }}</ref> while Dave Meikleham from GamesRadar listed his appearance as one of the biggest plot twists in a video game because the trailers did not show him. Meikleham also called Raiden a \"surprisingly likeable character\" and found his dynamic with Solid Snake appealing.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 7 ... Games with mega plot twists you never saw coming |author=Meikleham, Dave |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/the-top-7-games-with-mega-plot-twists-you-never-saw-coming/a-2010111116427795018/g-2005120719070989166259/p-2 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404081240/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/the-top-7-games-with-mega-plot-twists-you-never-saw-coming/a-2010111116427795018/g-2005120719070989166259/p-2/ |archivedate=April 4, 2016 }}</ref> \n\nBefore joining [[Kojima Productions]], Ryan Payton stated that he was not disappointed by Raiden's introduction and liked the fact the ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' team kept his identity secret.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/interview-kojima-productions-ryan-payton?pager.offset=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019183937/http://www.1up.com/features/interview-kojima-productions-ryan-payton?pager.offset=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|title=Kojima Productions' Ryan Payton|author=Berghammer, Billy|website=1UP.com|accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref> Raiden's English voice actor [[Quinton Flynn]] was surprised by fans' response to the character but said it attracted new fans to the series. Flynn thought fans were angry at the idea that Raiden would replace Snake for all subsequent games.<ref name=\"gamingliberty\" /> Raiden's relationship with Rosemary was listed as the most awkward part of the ''Metal Gear'' series by [[1UP.com]], with writer Scott Sharkey speculating about Hideo Kojima's life because he said the relationship is autobiographical.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear's Top 5 Awkward Moments|website=1UP.com|date=June 3, 2011|author=Sharkey, Scott|url=http://www.1up.com/features/metal-gear-top-5-awkward|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019163635/http://www.1up.com/features/metal-gear-top-5-awkward|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref> '\n\nResponse to the character in subsequent games was mainly positive. ''GamePro''{{'}}s Pattrick Shaw analyzed his new design for ''Metal Gear Solid 4''; he said Raiden \"was in one hell of a fight\".<ref name=\"gamepro\"/> Raiden's redesign has been praised for reducing his androgynous appearance, thus making him more appealing.<ref>{{cite web |title=The complete history of Metal Gear |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/the-complete-history-of-metal-gear/a-2010100413446869097/g-20100610112655981027/p-3 |accessdate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315210142/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/the-complete-history-of-metal-gear/a-2010100413446869097/g-20100610112655981027/p-3/ |archivedate=March 15, 2016 }}</ref> UGO placed Raiden's design in that game at 18th on its 2011 list of \"the most stylin' alternate costumes\",<ref>{{cite web |title=The Most Stylin' Alternate Costumes |publisher=UGO Networks |date=February 27, 2011 |author=Jensen, K. Thor |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/raiden-ezio |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304144503/http://www.ugo.com/games/raiden-ezio |archivedate=2011-03-04 }}</ref> but Gavin Mackenzie from ''PLAY'' listed it seventh on his list of inappropriate outfits, stating that the costume was \"cool\" but had unnecessary accessories.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 inappropriate outfits |publisher=Play |author=Mackenzie, Gavin |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-10-inappropriate-outfits/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503231627/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-10-inappropriate-outfits/ |archivedate=May 3, 2011 }}</ref> It has also been compared with [[Gray Fox (Metal Gear)|Gray Fox]]'s cybernetic-ninja design in ''[[Metal Gear Solid (1998 video game)|Metal Gear Solid]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top ten ninjas on PlayStation |publisher=Play |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-ten-ninjas-on-playstation/ |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313155314/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-ten-ninjas-on-playstation/ |archivedate=March 13, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Metal Gear Villains |website=IGN |author=Scheeden, Jeese |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/881/881015p8.html |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628231830/http://stars.ign.com/articles/881/881015p8.html |archivedate=June 28, 2012 }}</ref> GameSpot staff stated that Raiden \"is definitely the inheritor of the quasi-unkillable [[Cyborg Ninja]] inheritance\" when he made his first appearance in a ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' trailer. GameSpot applauded his actions in the trailer, calling it \"wordlessly awesome\" and comparing his stunts with those in the film ''[[Casshan: Robot Hunter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 06: Metal Gear Solid 4 Extended Trailer Impressions|website=GameSpot |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/metalgearsolid4/news/6149999/e3-06-metal-gear-solid-4-extended-trailer-impressions?mode=previews|date=May 10, 2006|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> Writers from Cheat Code Central referred to his fight against Vamp in another trailer as the \"undeniable highlight\" that would make player wish to use Raiden in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots Trailer Analysis |publisher=Cheat Code Central |url=http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/metalgearsolid4gunsofthepatriotstrailer2.html |author1=Beatty, D'Marcus |author2=Walker, Matthew |accessdate=August 8, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601150415/http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/metalgearsolid4gunsofthepatriotstrailer2.html |archivedate=June 1, 2012 }}</ref> \n\nDave Meikleham of GamesRadar wrote an article titled \"Why ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'' [''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance''] will make you love Raiden\", writing that fans who disliked the character would find him appealing in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 09: Why Metal Gear Solid: Rising will make you love Raiden |publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/f/e3-09-why-metal-gear-solid-rising-will-make-you-love-raiden/a-2009060216521843009|author=Miekleham, Dave|accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> Raiden's role and development in ''Revengeance'' were found to be appealing, with GameSpot's Peter Brown praising his violent attitude that made him an outstanding anti-hero,<ref name=\"gspotreview\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=February 19, 2013 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review-6404028/ |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |website=GameSpot |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220060642/http://www.gamespot.com/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review-6404028/ |archive-date=2013-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> whereas [[GameTrailers]] wrote that Raiden contrasted with his ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' persona that was criticized in 2001.<ref name=\"gametrailers\">{{cite web |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/ux8c59/metal-gear-rising--revengeance-review |publisher=GameTrailers |date=February 19, 2013 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222053842/http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/ux8c59/metal-gear-rising--revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-22 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' said Raiden was now worthy of his own game based on his characterization.<ref name=\"Escapistreview\">{{cite web |last=Concepci\u00f3n |first=Miguel |date=February 19, 2013 |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/editorials/reviews/10193-Metal-Gear-Rising-Revengeance-Review-Outside-the-Box.2 |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance Review \u2013 Outside the Box |work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208103114/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/editorials/reviews/10193-Metal-Gear-Rising-Revengeance-Review-Outside-the-Box.2 |archive-date=2013-12-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Polygon'' said that while Raiden's actions provide a departure from the stealth games, his actions were referred as \"outlandish and ridiculous\". The detail given to Raiden's past was also praised.<ref name=\"polygon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/19/4002956/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review|title=''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review: blood and thunder'' review|work=Polygon|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|accessdate=1 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421085839/http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/19/4002956/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review|archive-date=2015-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> IGN wrote that fans of ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' would enjoy the game more because Raiden can replicate his moves from that game's cutscenes in gameplay.<ref name=\"IGNreview\">{{cite web |last=Dyer |first=Mitch |date=February 18, 2013 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/19/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |website=IGN |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221133025/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/19/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Eurogamer said a major change in Raiden's characterization is ''Revengeance'', referring to him as a \"the ultimate cyborg and also the ultimate killer\" based on his darker persona that is explored in combat.<ref name=\"eurogamerreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-02-19-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |website=[[Eurogamer]] |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=February 20, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219111713/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-02-19-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The idea of Raiden primarily using his sword to counterattack firepower was found appealing by ''Complex'' due to how ''Revengeance'' explores the soldier as a melee fighter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/02/10-things-you-should-know-about-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/no-guns|title=10 Things You Should Know About Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|website=Complex|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Flynn's performance earned mixed response due to the tones he gives Raiden when interacting with allies and enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cgmagonline.com/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/|title=METAL GEAR RISING: REVENGEANCE (XBOX 360) REVIEW|website=CGMagonline|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"eurogamerreview\"/>\n\n===Popularity===\n[[File:Metal Gear Rising promotion art.jpg|thumb|upright|Raiden's artwork used as a promotional piece in Leeds, UK, for ''Revengeance''.]]\n''[[Play (UK magazine)|PLAY]]'' editor Nick Jones listed the scene in which Raiden is nude as his fourth-favorite moment of the franchise, calling it the \"one of the funniest moments in gaming history\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid \u2013 My Top Five Moments |publisher=Play |author=Jones, Nick |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/editors-blog/metal-gear-solid-%e2%80%93-my-top-five-moments/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928184333/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/editors-blog/metal-gear-solid-%E2%80%93-my-top-five-moments/ |archivedate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref> Lisa Foiles of ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' included him on her 2014 list of top five katana wielders, writing \"this is not a popularity contest and Raiden qualifies\" even in ''MGS2'' where \"he was whiny, an emo, and kind of a bitch\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Top 5 Katana Wielders |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/9182-Top-5-Katana-Wielders |title=Top 5 Katana Wielders &#124; Top 5 with Lisa Foiles Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist |publisher=Escapistmagazine.com |accessdate=2014-06-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523220120/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/9182-Top-5-Katana-Wielders |archivedate=2014-05-23 }}</ref> Raiden proved to be more popular in Japan; according to [[Yoji Shinkawa]] this was because he matched the stereotype of the [[manga]] hero.<ref>{{cite web|title=The art of Metal Gear: Yoji Shinkawa's visual legacy |website=VG247 |date=April 24, 2013 |author=Cook, Dave |url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/04/23/the-art-of-metal-gear-yoji-shinkawas-visual-legacy/ |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426004119/http://www.vg247.com/2013/04/23/the-art-of-metal-gear-yoji-shinkawas-visual-legacy/ |archivedate=April 26, 2013 }}</ref> \n\n''[[Game Informer]]'' placed him on \"The Snubbed List\" of the best characters of the 2000s in response to his new design because it made fans like the idea of a new ''Metal Gear'' game solely focused on Raiden.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Snubbed List |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2010/11/19/the-snubbed-list.aspx |magazine=Game Informer |author=Bertz, Matt |date=November 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210154112/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2010/11/19/the-snubbed-list.aspx |archivedate=February 10, 2011 }}</ref>  In a 2010 ''[[Famitsu]]'' readers' poll, Raiden was voted the 42nd most-popular video game character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3177896 |title=Snake Beats Mario, Is Coolest Video Game Character Ever |author=Glifford, Kevin |website=[[1UP.com]] |accessdate=March 10, 2010 |date=February 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307232332/http://www.1up.com/do/newsstory?cid=3177896 |archivedate=March 7, 2016 }}</ref> ''[[GamePro]]'' called Raiden's encounter with Vamp in this game one of the \"most memorable cinematics\" of the series because of his change of fighting style from his debut as he \"redeems his girlish image\",<ref name=\"gamepro\">{{cite magazine|title=Feature: Metal Gear Solid Rising: 6 Things to Expect from the Game |magazine=GamePro|date=June 11, 2009 |author=Shaw, Pattrick|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/210813/metal-gear-solid-rising-6-things-to-expect-from-the-game/|accessdate=June 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628070625/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/210813/metal-gear-solid-rising-6-things-to-expect-from-the-game/|archivedate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> while [[IGN]] listed it as the 80th best moment in video-game history for similar reasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Video Game Moments |website=IGN |url=http://www.ign.com/top/video-game-moments/89 |accessdate=March 2, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303000639/http://www.ign.com/top/video-game-moments/89 |archivedate=March 3, 2012 }}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' ranked Raiden as the 12th-greatest soldier in video games, \"even as he's not as cool as Solid Snake\",<ref>\nChad Hunter, Michael Rougeau, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/05/the-50-greatest-soldiers-in-video-games/raiden The 50 Greatest Soldiers In Video Games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106064739/http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/05/the-50-greatest-soldiers-in-video-games/raiden |date=2013-11-06 }} , Complex.com, May 25, 2013.</ref> while GamesRadar called ''Revengeance'' \"perhaps the greatest cyborg ninja game of all time\".<ref name=gr>{{cite web|author=Henry Gilbert |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/deadliest-cyborg-ninjas-gaming-history/ |title=The deadliest cyborg ninjas in gaming history |publisher=GamesRadar |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007212618/http://www.gamesradar.com/deadliest-cyborg-ninjas-gaming-history/ |archivedate=2013-10-07 }}</ref> ''[[Play (UK magazine)|PLAY]]'' ranked Raiden as the second-top ninja in games.<ref name=play>''PLAY'' 232, page 34.</ref> While surpassed by Solid Snake, GamesRadar listed Raiden as the second-best video game hero of all time.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-video-game-heroes/|title=2. Raiden (Metal Gear)|publisher=GamesRadar|accessdate=September 22, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121205033358/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-video-game-heroes/|archive-date=2012-12-05|url-status=live}}\n</ref> In 2012, [[manga artist]] [[Hiro Mashima]] drew an illustration of Raiden in anticipation of the series' following games. He mentioned having had difficulties illustrating the character.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 09: Why Metal Gear Solid: Rising will make you love Raiden |publisher=Siliconera |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2012/09/04/fairy-tail-artist-is-excited-by-metal-gear-solid-news-draws-raiden/ |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=September 6, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907155342/http://www.siliconera.com/2012/09/04/fairy-tail-artist-is-excited-by-metal-gear-solid-news-draws-raiden/ |archivedate=September 7, 2012 }}</ref> Following ''Metal Gear Solid 4''{{'}}s release, Raiden also appeared in more lists. IGN's Jesse Schedeen listed Raiden as one of the \"gaming icons\" and [[most valuable player]]s of 2009, in response to his role in an upcoming ''Metal Gear'' title.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Cast of Characters: GDC '09 |website=IGN |date=March 30, 2009 |author=Schedeen, Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/967/967836p2.html |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204221908/http://stars.ign.com/articles/967/967836p2.html |archivedate=December 4, 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The MVP's of E3 2009 |website=IGN |author=Schedeen, Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/992/992651p3.html |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204065533/http://stars.ign.com/articles/992/992651p3.html |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref> [[Den of Geek]] listed Raiden as one of the most sexually appealing video game characters, calling him disappointing to some but to others \"a pin-up forever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/games/11632/top-10-sexiest-computer-game-characters |title=Top 10 sexiest computer game characters|author=Haigh, Matthew |publisher=Den of Geek|date=July 31, 2008|accessdate=August 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616015341/http://www.denofgeek.com/games/11632/top-10-sexiest-computer-game-characters|archive-date=2012-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn promoting ''Revengeance'', Raiden's design by Shinkawa was used in presence in London, Leeds and Liverpool during 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.endoftheline.co/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-mural/|title=METAL GEAR RISING : REVENGEANCE MURAL|website=End of the Line|date=12 February 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Voice actor [[Reuben Langdon]] described Raiden as a character he always wanted to play as most notably on ''Super Smash Bros''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meristation.as.com/zonaforo/topic/2207133/|title=Reuben Langdon (doblador Raiden) \"confiesa\" haber doblado a \u00e9ste en Super Smash Bros|website=Meristation|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Analysis===\nRaiden's role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' has been analyzed by several writers, who said he is intended to represent the player.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=87|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David }}</ref> Early in the game, when Raiden's [[virtual reality]] training is mentioned, the game shows scenes from the previous game ''[[Metal Gear Solid (1998 video game)|Metal Gear Solid]]'' in which the player takes control of Solid Snake.<ref>{{cite book|title=Joystick soldiers: the politics of play in military video games|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RTPmwwL63iwC&pg=PA263&dq=Raiden+Metal+Gear#v=onepage&q=Raiden%20Metal%20Gear&f=false|pages=263\u2013264|publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=August 8, 2009|isbn=978-0-415-99660-0|author=Huntemann, Nina B.}}</ref> Raiden's interactions with veteran Solid Snake identify the former as \"a ''Metal Gear'' fan\". As the game progresses it is stated that Raiden \"has become Snake\", having developed skills similar to those he gained from taking part in the Big Shell's fights that resemble ''Metal Gear Solid''{{'}}s Shadow Moses Island.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=87\u201388|publisher=Lexington Books|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David}}</ref> The recurring plot twist involving Raiden's life and the people with whom he often interacts have been praised as being early post-truth content in a video game. Raiden's interaction with the Patriots was also analyzing the way the digital era became relevant over a decade after ''Sons of Liberty'' was released.<ref name=\"glixel\">{{cite web |author=Wiltshire, Alex|url=http://www.glixel.com/news/how-metal-gear-solid-2-foretold-our-post-truth-future-w450225 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119172715/http://www.glixel.com/news/how-metal-gear-solid-2-foretold-our-post-truth-future-w450225 |title=Flashback: How 'Metal Gear Solid 2' Foretold Our Post-Truth Future |archive-date=19 November 2016 |website=Glixel |url-status=dead |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>https://nowloading.co/posts/4199069/amp</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/the-scary-political-relevance-of-metal-gear-solid-2 |title=The Scary Political Relevance of 'Metal Gear Solid 2' |author=Kunzelman, Cameron |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=2018-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223120038/https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/the-scary-political-relevance-of-metal-gear-solid-2 |archive-date=2017-02-23 |url-status=live}}</ref> Raiden's development in ''Sons of Liberty'' were becomes a stronger soldier for imitating Snake's role in ''Metal Gear Solid'' was retold in ''The Phantom Pain'' when the player learns their character, [[Venom Snake]], is not the famous Big Boss but instead a doctor who was hypnotized into being a double of the mercenary across the video game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://webnewtype.com/special/metalgear/en_01/|title=Manabu Makime & Hitori Nojima Metal Gear discussion vol.1|website=Newtype|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLater in the game, a character tells Raiden to \"turn off the console\", which confuses both Raiden and the player; this was first interpreted as a [[fourth wall]]-breaking joke but the game's climax goes deeper into Raiden's connection with the player.<ref name=\"avatarsofstory\"/> When his superiors force Raiden to kill the game's antagonist, Solidus Snake, the designers tell the player to finish the game.<ref name=Weise>{{cite web|title=How Videogames Express Ideas |author=Matthew Weise |work=Level Up: Digital Games Research Conference |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |year=2003 |url=http://www.digra.org/dl/db/05150.07598.pdf |accessdate=November 21, 2009 |page=13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415123434/http://www.digra.org/dl/db/05150.07598.pdf |archivedate=April 15, 2010 }}</ref> Both the player and Raiden take different paths at the game's end; the player is told not to waste time playing games<ref name=\"avatarsofstory\">{{cite book|title=Avatars of story|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dzX3n66QRiEC&pg=PA225&dq=Raiden+Metal+Gear#v=onepage&q=Raiden%20Metal%20Gear&f=false|page=225|publisher=[[University Of Minnesota Press]]|author=Ryan, Marie-Laure|isbn=978-0-8166-4686-9}}</ref> while Raiden's character is expanded with his decision to move on with his life, rejecting his previous identity by discarding the [[dog tag]]s the player wore in the beginning.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=89|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David }}</ref> \n\nUpon the revelation of Raiden's new design as a cyborg ninja, writers said he distanced himself from his previous appearance that imitated Solid Snake.<ref name=\"playingwithvideogames\"/> Raiden's increasingly masculine redesigns following his debut were noted be a leaning to Western heroes in gaming despite Raiden retaining his original characterization by Todd Harper in the book ''Queerness in Play''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Queerness in Play|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2018|isbn=978-3319905419|page=152|author=Harper, Todd}}</ref> IGN also said Raiden becomes a different type of game hero with a new, direct fighting style.<ref name=\"gamepro\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.ign.com/articles/121/1214596p1.html |title=Opinion: Revengeance Will Ruin Metal Gear Solid |website=IGN |author=George, Richards |date=December 12, 2011 |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122062359/http://games.ign.com/articles/121/1214596p1.html |archivedate=January 22, 2012 }}</ref> being instead compared with the lead characters from ''[[Devil May Cry]]'' and ''[[God of War (franchise)|God of War]]''  favorably due to how they fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/stop-your-delusional-whining-platinums-metal-gear-rising-best-thing-could-have-happened/ |title=Stop your delusional whining: Platinum's Metal Gear Rising is the best thing that could have happened |publisher=GamesRadar |author=Houghton, David |date=December 13, 2011 |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220031736/http://www.gamesradar.com/stop-your-delusional-whining-platinums-metal-gear-rising-best-thing-could-have-happened/ |archivedate=February 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/meristation/2012/12/11/avances/1355245200_111196.html|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance, Impresiones|website=Meristation|date=2 July 2017|accessdate=April 5, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Metal Gear characters|List of ''Metal Gear'' characters]]\n*[[Ninja in popular culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/originals/catching-up-to-metal-gear-rising-raiden-s-story-so-far|title=Catching up to Metal Gear Rising: Raiden's story so far\n|publisher=GameZone|date=February 3, 2013|author=Faciane, Alex}}\n{{portal bar|Japan|Speculative fiction|Video games}}\n{{Metal Gear}}\n\n[[Category:Adoptee characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Hideo Kojima]]\n[[Category:Characters designed by Yoji Shinkawa]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Cyborg characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]] <!--Even if he's not actually black, he was still born in Liberia/Africa.-->\n[[Category:Fictional characters with multiple personalities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n[[Category:Fictional child soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Army Delta Force personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional First Liberian Civil War veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional immigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Fictional Liberian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional private military members]]\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional super soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Konami protagonists]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional mercenaries in video games]]\n[[Category:Metal Gear characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional military personnel in video games]]\n[[Category:Ninja characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional secret agents and spies in video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale fighters]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with electric or magnetic abilities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Character in Metal Gear}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Raiden (''Metal Gear'')}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n|name= Raiden\n|image= Raiden MGS2.png\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= Raiden, as portrayed in a promotional CGI render for ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]''.\n|first = ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' (2001)\n| last = ''[[Super Bomberman R]]'' (2018)\n|series= [[Metal Gear]]\n|creator= [[Hideo Kojima]]\n|designer= [[Yoji Shinkawa]]\n|voice= [[Quinton Flynn]]<br />[[Charlie Schlatter]] (''[[Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater#Subsistence|MGS3]]'' Secret Theater)<br/>[[Kenyu Horiuchi]] (Japanese)\n|motion_actor= Eiji Morisaki (''MGS2'') <br/> Takeshi Yoshioka (''MGS4'')\n|nationality= [[Liberian Americans|American-Liberian]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2012/11/22/metal-gear-rising-main-cyborgs-explained-alliances-weapons-and-abilities/ |title=Metal Gear Rising main cyborgs explained \u2013 alliances, weapons and abilities |magazine=[[PlayStation Official Magazine - UK|PlayStation Official Magazine]] |author=Hurley, Leon |date=November 22, 2012 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127213241/http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2012/11/22/metal-gear-rising-main-cyborgs-explained-alliances-weapons-and-abilities/ |archivedate=November 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n| family             = Solidus Snake (guardian), Rosemary (wife), John (son)\n|affiliation= [[FOXHOUND|Pseudo-FOXHOUND]] operative unknowingly employed by [[The Patriots (Metal Gear)|The Patriots]] (''MGS2'')<br/>Free agent (''MGS4'', Post-MGRR)<br/>Cyborg private military contractor (''MGRR'')\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Raiden'''|\u96f7\u96fb|lead=yes}}, real name {{nihongo|Jack|\u30b8\u30e3\u30c3\u30af|Jakku}}, is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] and one of the main protagonists of [[Konami]]'s ''[[Metal Gear]]'' series of video games. The character was created by [[Hideo Kojima]] and designed by [[Yoji Shinkawa]], and was introduced in the series as the main [[player character]] of the 2001 [[stealth game]] ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]''. In ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', Raiden appears to be a member of the U.S. special operations unit [[FOXHOUND]] and is participating in his first mission against terrorists. Despite coming across as a rookie, he is a young soldier who is later revealed to have been a Liberian [[child soldier]]. Raiden also appears as a supporting character in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots]]'', in which he is assisting the series' protagonist [[Solid Snake]] in his fight against [[Revolver Ocelot]]'s forces. He is also the main character of the [[hack and slash]] game ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'', in which he is dealing with his past and his present life as a combatant who faces enemies from [[private military companies]].\n\nRaiden, who was inspired by the [[Sherlock Holmes]] stories and a fan's letter wanting a younger character to be featured in the series, originated from Hideo Kojima's desire to view Solid Snake from a different point of view. Raiden's inclusion in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' was kept secret from gamers before his debut; despite some players' reactions, the staff liked the character. To appeal to fans of the series who initially disliked Raiden, the character was redesigned for ''Metal Gear Solid 4''. He was again redesigned for both the cancelled game ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'' and its reboot ''Revengeance'' to portray a darker side of his character. In Japanese, the character is voiced by  [[Kenyu Horiuchi]] and in English by [[Quinton Flynn]].\n\nRaiden's debut role as the protagonist of ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' was controversial, however, due to his unexpected substitution for the established hero Solid Snake. Some critics defended the character, stating that fans were merely angered by the former's removal and that the latter was appealing. Despite this mixed reception, Raiden has been praised for his role and ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' redesign especially in his fight scene, and more for his role and design in ''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance'' where he was found as a better character than in previous installments.\n\n==Character design==\n===Initial concept===\n{{multiple image\n | footer    = Hideo Kojima created Raiden while Yoji Shinkawa designed him.\n | image1    = Hideo Kojima - Tokyo Game Show 2011 (1) (cropped).jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  =  \n | width1    = 170\n | image2    = Yoji Shinkawa.png\n | alt2      =\n | caption2  =\n | width2    = 150\n}}\nAccording to series creator [[Hideo Kojima]], the decision to make a new character to replace Solid Snake for most of ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' stemmed from the developer's desire to develop Snake from a third-person perspective. Kojima stated that Raiden's character and his perception by the audience were important to the overall feel of the story. The idea of having a second main character was inspired by the [[Sherlock Holmes]] short stories and novels in which the narrator is [[Dr. Watson]] rather than Holmes. Kojima said Snake was the game's protagonist rather than Raiden. Yoshikazu Matsuhana, assistant director for the project, was uncertain about this decision; he considered Raiden a \"weak-looking character\" but decided to follow Kojima.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Final Hours of Metal Gear Solid 2|website=[[GameSpot]]|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/btg_mgs2/p02_01.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103100148/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/btg_mgs2/p02_01.html|accessdate=July 3, 2011|archivedate=January 3, 2006}}</ref> The codename \"Raiden\" was based on that of the [[Mitsubishi J2M|Mitsubishi J2M Raiden]], a historical combat aircraft of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service]]. It was initially planned to be written in [[katakana]] as \"\u30e9\u30a4\u30c7\u30f3\", but was changed to the [[kanji]] form \"\u96f7\u96fb\" because of a resemblance to [[Osama bin Laden|Bin Laden]]'s \"Laden\" in katakana, \"\u30e9\u30fc\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://m.kotaku.com/5844190/what-osama-bin-laden-and-metal-gear-solid-have-in-common|title=What Osama bin Laden and Metal Gear Solid Have in Common|date=September 27, 2011|website=[[Kotaku]] |author=Ashcraft, Brian|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref> His full name was going to be \"Raiden Brannigan\" but the idea was scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709185620/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|title=MGS2 PRODUCTION BACKGROUND NOTES|publisher=Shinobu Webs|archivedate=July 9, 2013|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> The romantic relationship between Raiden and Rosemary was inspired by Kojima's experiences; their names, Jack and Rose, are a reference to characters in the film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref name=\"Making\"/> In ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', Raiden is considered to be a representation of the player through the experiences between the player and the character during the game.<ref name=Howell>\n{{cite web |author1=James Howell |author2=Ryan Payton |lastauthoramp=yes |title=The Kojima Productions Report Session 084 |publisher=[[Kojima Productions]] |date=March 20, 2008 |url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2008/03/000153.html |accessdate=November 24, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604144853/http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2008/03/000153.html |archivedate=2009-06-04 }}</ref>\n\nKojima received much fan mail; one letter from a girl stated she did not want to play a game with an old man. Kojima took this into consideration; he and his team designed Raiden to be more appealing to women.<ref name=\"volone\"/> Designer [[Yoji Shinkawa]] said he and the other character designers took much inspiration for Raiden's appearance from the ''[[bish\u014dnen]]'' archetype.<ref name=\"volone\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 3: Subsistence|year=2006|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Metal Gear Saga Vol. 1}}</ref> Because Raiden was a new character, the staff designed him carefully, giving him white hair to symbolize his introduction. Shinkawa also said Raiden had an overall feminine appearance.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite video game|title=The Document of Metal Gear Solid 2|year=2002|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Making of Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty}}</ref> His outfit\u2014the Skull Suit\u2014was difficult to  design until the staff decided on a \"bonelike\" concept. Shinkawa wanted to make Raiden sexually appealing, emphasizing the tightness of his clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp/gs/game/mgs2/art/third.html |title=Yoji Shinkawa Interview: Segment 3 |publisher=[[Konami]] |accessdate=March 1, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019131636/http://www.konami.jp/gs/game/mgs2/art/third.html |archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref> The design of Raiden's aqua-mask was inspired by ancient mystical [[ninjutsu]], where the ninja bites a scroll in the mouth during magic transformations. Raiden's final duel with the boss Solidus Snake was revised in the making of the game. Originally, to defeat Solidus, Raiden must cut off both his mechanical snake-like arms, then he must attack Solidus' back and sever the back bone vertebra connection, rendering Solidus no longer mobile. Following this, Raiden would finish Solidus by decapitating him similar to samurai fashion. The scene was rejected and instead Raiden would slice Solidus' stomach, another idea taken from samurais. However, this concept was also scrapped to simply Raiden slicing Solidus' vertebral column with the boss falling from the area to give the idea he could not accept his defeat.<ref name=\"production\">{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709185620/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/production.html|title=Metal Gear Solid 2 Production|archivedate=July 9, 2013|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Konami]] kept Raiden's starring role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' secret until the game's North American release; the company replaced Raiden with Snake in teaser trailers and other preview materials. Although Raiden appeared in several preview trailers in his scuba gear, his presence was not emphasized.<ref name=\"Making\" /> The surprise to fans that Raiden was not Snake was admitted by Kojima to have been inspired by the plot twist of ''[[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]]'' where the titular character played by [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was not a villain in that movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/commentary2.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713081833/https://muni_shinobu.webs.com/mgs2/commentary2.html|title=Big Shell Infiltration \uff5e Contact Peter Stillman|publisher=Shinobu Wbes|archivedate=July 13, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Raiden's appearance in the game was announced to the Japanese press on the day of the game's release in North America.<ref>{{cite video game|title=The Document of Metal Gear Solid 2|year=2002|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote=}}</ref> Due to negative response to Raiden's role in the game, Kojima said in retrospective that the team failed to properly show the character.<ref name=\"spong\"/>\n\n===Further development===\nRaiden's new design for ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' was a response to the criticism that only his face remained in his cybernetic body. Shinkawa was surprised by the way he illustrated Raiden. The staff noted that Raiden's debut in the game's trailer received notably positive responses; several video-game magazines promoted the game with Raiden's screenshots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mp.i-revo.jp/user.php/kp-ryan/entry/52.html |title=The KP Report Session 027 |publisher=mp.i.revo |work=Kojima Productions Report |author=Payton, Ryan |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703183506/http://mp.i-revo.jp/user.php/kp-ryan/entry/52.html |archivedate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Shinkawa stated Raiden was remade as a darker hero to appeal to the Western fanbase. Seeing [[Gray Fox (Metal Gear)|Gray Fox]] as one of his favorite characters, Shinkawa made Raiden be an archetype of such character, making Raiden a cyborg like him.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.3djuegos.com/comunidad-foros/tema/21118594/0/el-arte-de-metal-gear-el-legado-visual-de-yoji-shinkawa/|title=[- El Arte de Metal Gear {{!}} El legado visual de Yoji Shinkawa |publisher=3DJuegos |language=  fr |accessdate= November 26, 2018}}</ref> Kojima echoed similar comments, indicating he wanted to expand the character with another game.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://gamerant.com/hideo-kojima-solid-snake-project-ogre-metal-gear-rising-ts-123571/ |title= Hideo Kojima Talks Killing Snake, Project Ogre, Metal Gear Rising & More! |publisher= GameRant |author=Schirado, Tyler |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate= February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120325151051/http://gamerant.com/hideo-kojima-solid-snake-project-ogre-metal-gear-rising-ts-123571/ |archivedate= March 25, 2012}}</ref> In designing him, Shinkawa wanted to convey both Raiden's beauty and sorrow in his cybernetic body. He was given the ability to wield swords with his own legs, giving the players the impression he was a ninja.<ref>{{cite book |title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots Master Art Works |year=2009 |asin=B0033910T0 |publisher=Example Product Manufacturer |page=39}}</ref> Raiden's first fight against [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Vamp|Vamp]] in the game caused motion and voice actors difficulty because of carefully planned movements performed by the two fighters. The staff was satisfied with the outcome, considering it one of the best battles in the game.<ref name=\"solidfourmaking\">{{cite video|title=Making of Metal Gear Solid 4|medium=Blu-ray|publisher=Konami Digital Entertainment GmbH|date=2008}}</ref> Two actors were selected for the motion capture of Raiden; one did most of his appearances while another did his action sequences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp:80/mgs4/us/interview/02.html|title=Development|publisher=Konami|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427133319/http://www.konami.jp/mgs4/us/interview/02.html|archivedate=April 27, 2009|accessdate=September 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Raiden's fights in ''Guns of the Patriots'' were made to assist the weaker Solid Snake and appealed to previous fans of the series who disliked the character.<ref name=\"spong\">{{cite web|url=https://spong.com/feature/10110941/Interview-Hideo-Kojima-on-Metal-Gear-Rising/2|title=Interviews// Hideo Kojima on Metal Gear Rising|publisher=Spong|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128034922/https://spong.com/feature/10110941/Interview-Hideo-Kojima-on-Metal-Gear-Rising/2|archive-date=2018-11-28|url-status=live}}\n</ref> Because Raiden became a more active character in ''Guns of the Patriots'', Kojima expressed a desire in him returning in a future character as playable.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors\"/>\n\n[[File:Atsushi Inaba (cropped).jpg|thumb|Atsushi Inaba from Platinum Games oversaw Raiden's character in ''Rising'']]\nWhen ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'' was known as ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'', former producer Shigenobu Matsuyama hinted that Raiden's past as a child soldier would be elaborated upon and his weaknesses as a human would be explored. Matsuyama wanted Raiden to have as strong a role in the game as in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', leading him to become its main character.<ref name=\"eurogamer interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-13-metal-gear-solid-rising-interview?page=1 |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising Interview |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Wesley Yin-Poole |date=September 13, 2010 |accessdate=September 14, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917210657/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-13-metal-gear-solid-rising-interview?page=1 |archivedate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> Director [[Mineshi Kimura]] wanted Raiden to be able to move the way he did in the ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' trailers, wanting to show \"the stealth of the sword, and the strength of not even losing to the gun, and the fear and power you have with this blade\".<ref name=\"E32010 liveblog\" /> Matsuyama said they would focus on Raiden's strong will and physical strength so he would be enjoyable to control.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/pc/metal_gear_solid_rising/preview-2640.html |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising Preview |publisher=VideoGamer.com |author=Gatson, Martin |date=August 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003103501/http://www.videogamer.com/pc/metal_gear_solid_rising/preview-2640.html |archivedate=2012-10-03}}</ref> Raiden's design was changed during the game's development, leading to different promotional images of him.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://m.kotaku.com/5460065/metal-gear-solid-risings-raiden-has-changed |title=Metal Gear Solid: Rising's Raiden Has Changed|website=[[Kotaku]] |author=McWhertor, Michael |date=January 29, 2010  |accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref> Following the game's reboot into a spin-off, developers stated that while Raiden \"has grown up\" in comparison to previous ''Metal Gear'' games, he is still conflicted with his life as a child soldier in the [[First Liberian Civil War]], leading him to become a \"dark hero\".<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edge-online.com/news/e3-2012-platinum-details-metal-gear-rising-revengeance |title=E3 2012: Platinum details Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance |publisher=Edge |date=June 1, 2012 |accessdate=June 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604012444/http://www.edge-online.com/news/e3-2012-platinum-details-metal-gear-rising-revengeance |archivedate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Shinkawa designed Raiden's new body to emphasize his dark heroism, contrasting with his ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' persona. Shimkawa later discussed with Platinum Games' Kenji Saito about including his quasi-human look. Raiden's loss of an eye also represents his transformation across the story while also comparing him with the previous antagonist [[Solidus Snake]]. Tamari also explained that the cybernetic functions Raiden has was based on research led by the [[University of Texas]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance The Complete Official Guide|publisher=Piggyback |year=2013|isbn=978-0307897169}}</ref> In response to complaints that ''Rising'' appeared to contradict Raiden's ending in ''Guns of the Patriots'', the Kojima Productions staff said the game would explain what happened with Raiden's life.<ref name=\"session153\">{{cite web|title=Kojima Productions Podcast Session 153 |publisher=Kojima Productions |date=January 26, 2012 |url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2012/01/ |accessdate=December 29, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407190933/http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog_e/2012/01/ |archivedate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> While Steven Armstrong was the game's final antagonist, the character of Jetstream Sam was developed to be Raiden's rival, something Shinkawa and fellow designer Kenichirou Yoshimura worked together to make both of them contrast each other through their visual appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://platinumgames.com/2012/12/27/staying-true-to-metal-gear/|title=Statying True to Metal Gear|website=Platinum Games |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231161729/http://platinumgames.com/2012/12/27/staying-true-to-metal-gear/ |archivedate=December 31, 2012 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe team in charge of ''Revengeance'' depicted Raiden as a more mature character than in his previous appearances; they said his swordplay is not based on any samurai and that Raiden's cybernetic body includes heels because they \"are very uncomfortable to run in or fight in&nbsp;... and besides he's a guy!\".<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2012/06/11/metal-gear-rising-preview-and-interview-platinum-medal-463731/|title=Metal Gear Rising preview and interview \u2013 Platinum medal|publisher=Metro|date=June 11, 2012|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128034925/https://metro.co.uk/2012/06/11/metal-gear-rising-preview-and-interview-platinum-medal-463731/|archive-date=2018-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref> When developing the game's, the team thought of Raiden's revenge against his enemies, which resulted in the title \"Reveangeance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-story-of-the-chemical-reaction-that-gave-metal-gear-rising-its-revengeance|title=The story of the 'chemical reaction' that gave Metal Gear Rising its Revengeance|newspaper=Financial Post|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Writer Etsu Tamari expressed joy in the final product and expected that in the future, the team could make another game focused on Raiden.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/3/6/4070250/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-writer-on-future-dlc-and-how-the-story|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance writer on future DLC and how the story got shifted years into the future|website=Polygon|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210063241/https://www.polygon.com/2013/3/6/4070250/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-writer-on-future-dlc-and-how-the-story|archive-date=2018-12-10|url-status=live}}\n</ref> In a further analysis of how to write Raiden in ''Revengeance'', Tamari stated he needed a new character that would bring him support in the form of the dog-like robot named Bladewolf; Similar to how Snake guides Raiden in ''Sons of Liberty'', the mature Raiden acts like a mentor to Bladewolf across the story resulting in his character arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/noticias/dos-dlc-metal-gear-rising-seran-precuelas-49082|title=Dos DLC de Metal Gear Rising ser\u00e1n precuelas|date=6 March 2013|publisher=Hobby Consolas|language=Spanish|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Writer Etsu Tamari wanted to portray Raiden as a more mature person who wishes to take Snake's footsteps.<ref name=\"gamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamer.ne.jp/news/201209270035/|website=Gamer|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 5, 2020|title=\u3010TGS 2012\u3011\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u306b\u96f7\u96fb\u5f79\u306e\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u3092\u8fce\u3048\u3001\u300c\u65ac\u308b\u300d\u6c17\u6301\u3061\u826f\u3055\u304b\u3089\u96f7\u96fb\u306e\u5fc3\u306e\u845b\u85e4\u306a\u3069\u3001\u5236\u4f5c\u79d8\u8a71\u3082\u8a9e\u3089\u308c\u305f\u300c\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300d\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u30ec\u30dd}}</ref> [[Atsushi Inaba]] wanted the gameplay of ''Revengeance'' fit Raiden's style of characterization, resulting in the use of parries rather than defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/77006/how-stealth-came-back-into-metal-gear-rising-revengeance|title=How stealth came back into Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|publisher=Shack News|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Inaba felt honored to work in ''Revengeance'' due to how he was able to see a more mature version of the character to the point of wishing for a sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/why-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-has-parrying-and-other-questions-for-platinumgames/|title=Why Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance Has Parrying And Other Qs For PlatinumGames\n|date=11 December 2012\n|publisher=Silicoenra|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> \n\nRaiden is first depicted as a white-haired adult who uses a protective suit known as a {{nihongo|\"Skull Suit\"|\u30b9\u30ab\u30eb\u30b9\u30fc\u30c4|Sukaru S\u016btsu}} for his missions.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' Your new Sneaking suit uses electrofiber technology, a by-product of fiber-optics research. The texture isn't far removed from rubber but the material protects against a wide range of toxic substances. The suit itself has a wide array of built-in sensors. It is referred to as \"Smart Skin\" in military R&D. Data about damage to different regions of the body, including blood loss, is exchanged between the suit and the intravenous nanomachines to create a bio-feedback system. ... They call this the \"Skull Suit\" in FOXHOUND.}}</ref> In ''Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots'' Raiden's entire body below the upper jaw is replaced with a prototype cybernetic body; his blood is replaced with a military substitute called {{nihongo|\"White Blood\"|\u767d\u8840|Shiro Chi}} that requires regular maintenance.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Naomi Hunter:''' That's right. Raiden's blood is an older type of artificial blood that was used by the military ... Called white blood. After it's been in use for a while, the blood needs to be dialyzed ... Filtered. Right now, he's slipping into autotoxemia.}}</ref> His original cybernetic body is replaced with a black one that also covers the left eye for ''Revengeance''.  Although proficient at all types of weaponry, Raiden specializes in wielding swords that resonate at high frequencies for the last fights in ''Sons of Liberty'',<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Olga asked me to give it to you. Besides, I'm not a big fan of blades.}}</ref> and during ''Guns of the Patriots'' and ''Revengeance''. {{Clear}}\n\n===Personality and portrayal===\n[[File:Quinton Flynn.jpg|thumb|upright|Quinton Flynn has enjoyed doing the English voice for Raiden.]]\n\nIn his first appearances Raiden is a rookie agent who is inexperienced as a result of training only in [[virtual reality]]. He later reveals, however, that he was a child soldier known as {{nihongo|\"[[Jack the Ripper]]\"|\u30b8\u30e3\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30ea\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc|Jakku Za Ripp\u0101}} who killed several enemies in a civil war and is ashamed of his past.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' No, it was field training, when I was a kid. I lied, Snake. I have more field experience than I can remember. It's not VR that's doing this to me. / '''Solid Snake:''' Raiden, we don't carry guns to take people down. We're not here to help some politician either. / '''Raiden:''' You can say that because you're a legend, a hero. I'm Jack the Ripper, a dirty reminder -- of a terrible mistake.}}</ref> This affects Raiden's personality; he begins to believe he is only useful in the battlefield and his relationship with his girlfriend [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Rosemary|Rosemary]] would not work.<ref name=\"war\"/><ref name=\"past\"/> Manipulation by the Patriots causes him to believe he has no free will. [[Solid Snake]] encourages Raiden to ignore what people tell him and to become self-reliant when problem-solving.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Listen, don't obsess over words so much. Find the meaning behind the words, then decide. You can find your own name. And your own future&nbsp;... I know you didn't have much in terms of choices this time. But everything you felt, thought about during this mission is yours. And what you decide to do with them is your choice ... / '''Raiden:''' You mean start over? / '''Solid Snake:''' Yeah, a clean slate. A new name, new memories. Choose your own legacy. It's for you to decide. It's up to you}}</ref> His original personality was that of a \"creep or a weirdo\", who licked bird doodoo but this was discarded by the staff.<ref name=\"production\"/>\n\nIn the Japanese versions of the games, Raiden has been voiced by [[Kenyu Horiuchi]],<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:\u5800\u5185 \u8ce2\u96c4 |publisher=Kenyu Office |language=Japanese |url=http://www.kenyu-office.com/profile/horiuchikenyu.html |accessdate=October 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928204054/http://www.kenyu-office.com/profile/horiuchikenyu.html |archivedate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> who first saw him as an attractive young man whose actions in ''Son of Liberty'' were challenging for his identity. Horiuchi was impressed by the characterization shown across the game, believing him to fit with other members featured in the game. Kojima liked Horiuchi's work, believing Raiden became popular in Japan in part because of his performance, something which he felt the character lacked in Western regions.<ref name=\"gamer\"/> could understand the character's pain; despite becoming a cyborg, Raiden still acts like a human.<ref name=\"solidfourmaking\"/> Horiuchi took a liking to Raiden's spin-off game, ''Revengeance'', as he acted as the lead for the first time but was still glad that he got meet new actors who appeared in the game, most notably the actor behind Doktor. THe actors also liked the inclusion of Raiden's sidekick, LQ-84i (later renamed Bladewolf), as they believe that ninjas like Raiden obligatory need dogs as allies. Another relationship the actors liked was Raiden's exchanges with Courtney due to few female characters being present in the game but felt they made the characters get along properly.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors\">{{cite web|url=https://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/538/538783/|title=\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u304c\u767b\u5834\uff01 \u6570\u3005\u306e\u5236\u4f5c\u79d8\u8a71\u304c\u660e\u304b\u3055\u308c\u305f\u300e\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300f\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8|website=Dengeki Online|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Horiuchi felt confident in being in doing Raiden's voice as the lead, believing his thirty years of experience made him suitable for the role.<ref name=\"revengeanceactors2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/201209/24021722.html|title=\u96f7\u96fb\u73fe\u308b\uff01\u3000\u5800\u5185\u8ce2\u96c4\u3055\u3093\u3092\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u306b\u8fce\u3048\u305f\u300e\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30ae\u30a2 \u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0 \u30ea\u30d9\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30f3\u30b9\u300f\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u3010TGS2012\u3011|website=Famitsu|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCasting director Kris Zimmerman chose [[Quinton Flynn]], with whom she had previously worked, to voice Raiden in the series' English adaptation. Flynn remembers having a long time to develop the character and being instructed by Zimmerman to use an older voice from a character he previously voiced. Flynn said Raiden was one of his favorite video-game voice characters and noted a difference between his roles in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' and ''Metal Gear Solid 4'';<ref name=\"gamingliberty\">{{cite web |title=Raiden Speaks! An interview with Quinton Flynn |publisher=The Gaming Liberty |date=May 21, 2011 |url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/05/21/raiden-speaks-an-interview-with-quinton-flynn-part-1/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625005316/http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/05/21/raiden-speaks-an-interview-with-quinton-flynn-part-1 |archivedate=June 25, 2011}}</ref> Flynn was pleased with working alongside [[David Hayter]] whom he often interacted while recording the game.<ref name=\"metalgearinfor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metalgearinformer.com/?p=19735|title=QUINTON FLYNN (RAIDEN): THE KOJIMA \u2013 KONAMI SPLIT IS UNFORTUNATE, BUT THE METAL GEAR SERIES SHOULD CONTINUE REGARDLESS|website=Metal Gear Informer|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The English voice recording was overlooked by Scott Dolph, who reported back saying the English voice for Raiden was more neutral than the original Japanese voice.<ref name=\"production\"/> For ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' Flynn used a deeper voice to match the cyborg Raiden in contrast to the original, youthful Raiden of ''Metal Gear Solid 2''. Flynn said the voice he used was \"grizzled, yeah\u2014but different enough from the style of Snake\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/06/20/mgs4s-raiden-speaks|title=MGS4's Raiden Speakes|date=June 18, 2008|website=IGN|accessdate=August 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816195559/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/06/20/mgs4s-raiden-speaks|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref> During development of ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'', Flynn was not informed about the work despite Raiden being in the trailer. As a result, Flynn kept low hopes in regards to the idea of being cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2011/05/23/raiden-voice-actor-in-the-dark-regarding-mgs-rising.aspx|title=Raiden Voice Actor \"In The Dark\" Regarding MGS: Rising|website=Game Informer|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Addressing ''Guns of the Patriots''{{'}}s Raiden as more agressive than the original one, Flynn stated his favorite take on the character was ''Revengeance''{{'}}s as it there he acted as a \"blend\" between the two incarnations. He felt honored for taking the role of Raiden again, having received a \"Behind The Voice Actors\" award for his work.<ref name=\"metalgearinfor\"/> In 2015, Flynn stated he was pleased with Raiden's role in ''Reveangence'' and that he would have liked a new sequel Raiden as the lead. Internal problems between Kojima Productions and Konami, however, left Flynn worried there might not be another game in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gamingbolt.com/konami-were-considering-metal-gear-rising-2-kojima-break-up-unfortunate-raidens-va|title=Konami Were Considering Metal Gear Rising 2, Kojima Break Up Unfortunate: Raiden's VA|publisher=Gaming Bolt|accessdate=December 3, 2018|author=Sinha, Ravi|date=May 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204102018/https://gamingbolt.com/konami-were-considering-metal-gear-rising-2-kojima-break-up-unfortunate-raidens-va|archive-date=2018-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKojima Productions compared the experiences and ways of thinking of Raiden and Solid Snake. During the game's climax, Raiden stays handcuffed until his final fight against [[Solidus Snake]]; Snake escapes from his handcuffs to follow [[Revolver Ocelot]], emphasizing Raiden's lack of freedom. Hideo Kojima compared Raiden and Snake with [[movie monsters]] [[King Kong]] and [[Godzilla]], respectively; the former was taken from his home and his nature changes upon meeting Rosemary, whereas the latter will continue fighting against mankind's menaces. Defeating Solidus, Snake encourages Raiden to trust himself and believe in his own choices. This is further addressed by the staff's motivation to make a new sequel to ''Metal Gear'' without Kojima.<ref name=\"Making\" /> Kojima also likened Raiden with [[John Rambo]] from the ''[[Rambo (film series)|Rambo]]'' series because both characters always find themselves taking part in battles despite their desire for a peaceful resolution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CVG_News/status/304968402521423872 |title=CVG News |publisher=Twitter |work=Computer and Video Games |date=February 22, 2013 |accessdate=March 3, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623151620/https://twitter.com/CVG_News/status/304968402521423872 |archivedate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> Raiden himself believes that he is destined to fight based on his upbringing during ''Revengeance'' while also following the concept of ''[[katsujinken]]'' in which samurai kill in order to protect the weak.<ref name=\"growth\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n{{multiple image\n | footer    = Raiden was designed as a cyborg in ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' (left) while in ''Rising'' his new appearance (right) was meant to emphasize his darker characterization.\n | image1    = MetalGearSolid4Raiden.png\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  =\n | width1    = 150\n | image2    = RaidenRevengeance.png\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  =\n | width2    = 240\n}}\n===Main games===\n''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' introduces the player to Raiden in the Plant chapter; Jack is introduced as a newly recruited, virtual reality-trained member of [[FOXHOUND]] with no live-combat experience before his current mission.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' Just a precaution. You are now designated \"Raiden.\" All right, Raiden. You've already covered infiltration in VR Training. / '''Raiden:''' I've completed three hundred missions in VR. I feel like some kind of legendary mercenary ...}}</ref> He is assisted via [[Receiver (radio)|Codec]] by his commanding officer the Colonel and his girlfriend Rosemary. Raiden's initial objective is to rescue several hostages from a terrorist group known as the Sons of Liberty.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' Jack, I'm a part of this mission. / '''Raiden:''' Colonel, what the hell is going on? / '''Colonel:''' Raiden, meet the mission analyst. She'll be overseeing the data saving and support.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel:''' You have two missions objectives. One: infiltrate the offshore decontamination facility \"Big Shell\" and safeguard the President and other hostages. And two: disarm the terrorists by any means necessary.}}</ref> During his mission, Raiden is helped by mercenary [[Solid Snake]] and spy [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Olga Gurlukovich|Olga Gurlukovich]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Olga:''' I was sent to provide you support. / '''Raiden:''' Support? Who sent you? The Colonel? / '''Olga:''' No ... the Patriots. ...My child is ... being held hostage by the Patriots.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Are you two really an NGO? / '''Otacon:''' Insofar as we're a nonprofit organization of civilians advocating a cause, yes. The cause happens to be the eradication of Metal Gear. / '''Solid Snake:''' We work on our own. But it's a cause worth fighting for.}}</ref>\n\nAs the story progresses, Jack is revealed to be a former child soldier who fought for the Sons of Liberty leader [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Solidus Snake|Solidus Snake]] during the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref name=\"war\"/><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solidus Snake:''' The eighties&nbsp;... the civil war. You were one of the best among the child soldiers that fought in that conflict. When you were barely ten years old, you became the leader of the small boys unit&nbsp;... I was your godfather, I named you.}}</ref> After the war's end, Raiden was given a normal life and tried to forget his past.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' When the civil war ended, those of us who survived were taken in by NGO's. They gave me a new life in the States. I can't complain. But nothing's changed&nbsp;... What I hate more than anything else in the world is my own past.}}</ref> It is revealed that a clandestine organization known as [[The Patriots (Metal Gear)|The Patriots]] is controlling his actions and his commanding officer is revealed as their computer-generated [[Artificial intelligence]] (AI).<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Otacon:''' I think it means&nbsp;... you've been talking to an AI. / '''Raiden:''' That's impossible! / '''Otacon:''' The Colonel probably isn't GW per se. GW was most likely stimulating cortical activity in the dormant part of your brain through signal manipulation of your own nanomachines. The Colonel is in part your own creation, cobbled together from expectations and experience&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Emma''': GW is a system that allows the Patriots to decide what will be recorded in tomorrow's history.}}</ref> One of their spies becomes Raiden's girlfriend and the two fall in love.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' No, it's something else. That day at Federal Hall two years ago&mdash;it wasn't a coincidence. I was ordered to keep an eye on you&nbsp;... / '''Raiden:''' Keep an eye on me? / '''Rosemary:''' Yes&mdash;by the Patriots. / '''Raiden:''' You're a spy;&nbsp;... / '''Rosemary:''' Jack, I thought I was acting, because that was my job. But I did fall in love with you, that wasn't an act.}}</ref> Raiden defeats Solidus after the Patriots' AIs tell him his death would also trigger those of Olga's child and Rosemary, the latter of whom is revealed to have been pregnant with Raiden's child during the mission.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Colonel''': It's time for the final exercise. Raiden, take Solidus down. / '''Raiden''': Think again! I'm through doing what I'm told! / '''Colonel''': Oh really? Aren't you forgetting something? \"If you die, my child dies.\" The termination of vital signals from your nanomachines means the death of Olga's child. Not to mention the death of Rose. She's wired the same way. / '''Raiden''': Rose -- does she actually exist? / '''Colonel''': (Using Rosemary's voice) Of course I do, Jack! You have to believe me! / '''Raiden''': Damn&nbsp;... / '''Colonel''': It will be a fight to the death.}}</ref> He later reunites with Rosemary, and both decide to stay together to raise their unborn child.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty|year=2001|developer=Konami Computer Entertainment Japan|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Of course. This is where we first met ... I remember now -- Today is the day I met you. That's it. I think I found something to pass along to the future. He said all living things want their genes to live on. / '''Rosemary:''' Are you talking about the baby? / '''Raiden:''' Yeah. But genes aren't the only thing you pass on. There are too many things that aren't written into our DNA. It's up to us to teach that to our children.}}</ref>\n\n''[[Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots]]'' (set five years after ''Metal Gear Solid 2'') features Raiden after rescuing Olga's daughter [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Sunny|Sunny]] from the Patriots,<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Solid Snake:''' Jack's gone? I used to work with the guy. He saved Sunny from the Patriots. / '''Roy Campbell:''' He disappeared soon after that.}}</ref> and searching for [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]]'s corpse for [[EVA (Metal Gear)|Big Mama]] in exchange.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Snake:''' Raiden, where have you been all this time? What have you been doing? Finding what? / '''Raiden:''' The corpse of Big Boss. / '''Snake:''' What? / '''Raiden:''' I was asked to do this in exchange for Sunny's location. / '''Snake:''' Matka Pluku ... Big Mama.}}</ref> The trauma of his breakup with Rosemary and the apparent miscarriage of his child have made Raiden believe he belongs on the battlefield.<ref name=\"war\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Rosemary:''' After the Big Shell Incident, he became unstable. Memories began to resurface from his childhood, when he fought for Solidus in the Liberian Civil War. And in the midst of all that ... The baby we had together&nbsp;... It hadn't even been born yet. Jack slowly stopped coming home. And when he did, he'd be dead drunk, sometimes covered in cuts and bruises.}}</ref><ref name=\"past\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' I've got nothing to lose. / '''Snake:''' Don't be an idiot. You know you've got someone to protect. / '''Raiden:''' It was never going to work out for me. It even \"rained\" the day I was born.}}</ref> Raiden is fitted with a cybernetic [[exoskeleton]] as a result of the Patriots' machinations;<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4 Database|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|level=Raiden}}</ref> he helps Solid Snake in the fight against [[Revolver Ocelot|Liquid Ocelot]], wanting to obtain the Patriots' powers. After several encounters with Liquid's men, Raiden stays in the ship ''Outer Haven'' to protect Snake as he shuts down the Patriots' AIs.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Snake:''' It's my duty to put an end to all of this. / '''Raiden:''' All right. I'll make sure they don't get through. / '''Otacon:''' Stay with me, Snake. Hold on until we insert the virus.}}</ref> In an epilogue, Rosemary tells Raiden their child was not miscarried; her marriage to [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Roy Campbell|Roy Campbell]] was a hoax to protect her and their son from the Patriots. Upon hearing this news, Raiden reconciles with Rosemary.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|year=2008|developer=Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' You said miscarriage&nbsp;... / '''Rosemary:''' I lied. I had a healthy baby boy. Roy pretended to by my husband&nbsp;... To protect me&nbsp;... And our son. Only until you'd completed your mission. To shield us from Patriot eyes&nbsp;... / '''Raiden:''' I'll never leave you alone again. Like a scene from Beauty and the Beast. / '''Rosemary:''' Don't say that. You're no beast. You're my husband. And his father. And me&nbsp;... I'm going to do my very best&nbsp;... to be the wife and mother this family deserves.}}</ref>\n\nRaiden returns as the main character in ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'', which is set four years after ''Metal Gear Solid 4''.<ref name=\"E32010 liveblog\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5565341/konami-e3-liveblog-is-right-here-hopefully-with-lightning-and-whips |title=Konami E3 Liveblog Is Right Here, Hopefully With Lightning And Whips |website=[[Kotaku]] |author=Stephen Totilo |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=June 16, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619063911/http://kotaku.com/5565341/konami-e3-liveblog-is-right-here-hopefully-with-lightning-and-whips |archivedate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> He is a member of the [[private military company]] (PMC) Maverick Security in multiple tasks while raising money for his family. They are attacked by a group of terrorists called Desperado Enforcement LLC that kill his protectee, N'ani, and leave Raiden near to death with mercenary Jeatstream Sam taking a liking to his fighting style.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Sam:''' Now I see. You deny your weapon its purpose! It yearns to bath in the blood of your enemies... but you hold it back! / '''Raiden:''' No... My sword is a tool of justice.}}</ref> He is saved by the elder scientist Wilhelm \"Doktor\" Voight and starts working with them to fight Desperado.<ref name=\"g4tv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/58828/official-e3-preview-of-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/ |title=Official E3 Preview of Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance |publisher=G4TV |date=June 4, 2012 |accessdate=August 29, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310115904/http://www.g4tv.com/videos/58828/official-e3-preview-of-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/ |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> Raiden fights Desperado's LQ-84i, an AI placed in a robot who works for Desperado but Raiden takes pity on it and has Doktor restore it under the name of Bladewolf who assists him.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Kevin:''' You sure you want the K-9000 there along for this one? / '''Raiden:''' I had the good Doktor make some adjustments along with the repairs. Remote wiping and AI wiping have been disabled. So yeah, so I say let's throw him a bone.}}</ref> Raiden's vengeful obsession with Desperado becomes personal when he discovers during a mission to Mexico that Desperado and World Marshal Inc have kidnapped several children, surgically removed their brains to place into cybernetic bodies, and were planning to subject them to VR training modeled on his own.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:'''Are they making these kids into cyborgs?}}</ref> Raiden then resigns from Maverick to pursue and retrieve the children's [[brain case]]s from World Marshal in Colorado, embracing his sadistic persona \"Jack the Ripper\" due to his constant struggles with Sam and Desperado's cyborg Moonsoon.<ref name=\"growth\">{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' You're right&nbsp;... about me, I mean. I knew something was&nbsp;... off. After the Patriots, I thought I could walk off the battlefield and into a normal life&nbsp;... but here I am, surrounded by death, arguing philosophy with terrorists. I told myself this was about justice, about protecting the weak&nbsp;... but I was wrong. / '''Monsoon:''' Then you admit it? / '''Raiden:''' I learned young that killing your enemies felt good. Really good. In America, my friends, my family&nbsp;... they helped me forget the devil inside&nbsp;... but who am I kidding? I was born to kill! The bit about my sword, that \"means of justice\" stuff? I guess I just needed something to keep \"the Ripper\" in check when I was knee-deep in bodies ... / '''Monsoon:''' You ... / '''Raiden:''' But you..all this ... is a wake-up call to what I really believe ... what I really am. / '''Monsoon:''' What are you saying / '''Raiden:''' I'm saying Jack is back!}}</ref> Raiden defeats Desperado and learns that Steven Armstrong was using PMCs to distract him as he attempts to create a new [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' I've taken Marshal HQ. / '''Boris:''' Raiden, what Sundowner said.  / '''Raiden:''' I know. Anything that'll rival 9-11 cannot be good... and in three hours}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Armstong:''' Trust me, a little war can work wonder. / '''Raiden:''' So grease the gears with some innocent blood, is that it? / '''Armstrong:''' Relax Jack. It's a war on terror. We're not to kill out civilians.}}</ref> When Bladewolf passes Raiden's the word of the late Sam, Raiden stops Armstrong's actions and decides not to return to Maverick and travels to the [[Middle East]] to battle World Marshal mercenaries.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Armstrong! I said my sword was a tool of justice. Not used in anger. Not used for vengeance. But now... Now I'm not so sure. And besides, this isn't my sword.}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|year=2012|developer=Platinum Games, Kojima Productions|publisher=Konami|quote='''Raiden:''' Sorry Boris. / '''Boris:''' I understand, but then ... what will you do? / '''Raiden:''' I've got my own war to fight.}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances ===\nRaiden does not appear in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater]]'' but he is parodied throughout the game by debuting character Raikov.<ref name=\"raikov\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.1up.com/features/saving-private-raiden?pager.offset=3|title=Saving Private Raiden|website=[[1UP.com]]|accessdate=June 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130116083043/http://www2.1up.com/features/saving-private-raiden?pager.offset=3|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> Raiden appears in a series of comical scenes in an early promotional trailer for ''Guns of the Patriots'', in which he fights for control of the franchise with Solid Snake. A sequel to the trailer titled \"Metal Gear Raiden: Snake Eraser\" was produced; Raiden travels to the past to assassinate [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]] but fails comically.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/metalgearsolid4/news/6133819/tgs-2005-metal-gear-raiden-snake-eraser?mode=news|title=TGS 2005: Metal Gear Raiden: Snake Eraser|website=[[GameSpot]] |author=Niizumi, Hirohiko |date=September 18, 2005 |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> In the trailer's English version, Raiden is voiced by [[Charlie Schlatter]] (the voice actor for Raikov) rather than Quinton Flynn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Charlie-Schlatter/|title=Charlie Schlatter|publisher=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Raiden's ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' version appears in the ''[[Metal Gear Solid: Portable Ops#Portable Ops Plus|Metal Gear Solid: Portable Ops Plus]]'' expansion pack as an unlockable character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/mgs-portable-ops-dated-nov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060438/http://www.1up.com/news/mgs-portable-ops-dated-nov|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 21, 2013|title=MGS: Portable Ops Plus Dated Nov. 13 for US|website=[[1UP.com]]|author=Pigna, Kris|date=October 17, 2007|accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref> His ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' incarnation appears as a playable character in ''[[Metal Gear Online]]''.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/metal-gear-online-adds-raiden|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019184939/http://www.1up.com/news/metal-gear-online-adds-raiden|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|title=Metal Gear Online adds Raiden, Vamp|website=[[1UP.com]]|author=Gifford, Kevin|date=February 18, 2009|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes]]'', Raiden stars in a non-canonical mission titled \"Jamais Vu\". Having time-travelled to the past,<ref>''Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes'' Jamais Vu trailer, Kojima Productions (2013).<br />'''Kazuhira Miller:''' But we've [MSF] got a secret weapon. A man [Raiden] from another world. A dark and distant future. A man turned into a war-machine with no human body for those bastards [body-snatchers] to snatch.</ref> he infiltrates Camp Omega under orders from [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Militaires Sans Frontieres|MSF]]. His aim is to incapacitate a group of soldiers known as the \"body snatchers\", a reference to the android replicators in Kojima's video game ''[[Snatcher (video game)|Snatcher]]''. His appearance in this game is modeled on that in ''Metal Gear Rising''.\n\nThe ''Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty'' 2007 [[comic book]] adaptation by Alex Garner retells Raiden's story with few changes. His relationship with Solidus is explored when he remembers his past; when Solidus about to kill him, Raiden is saved by Snake.<ref>{{cite book|title=Metal Gear Solid: Sons Of Liberty Volume 2|publisher=IDW Publishing |date=December 25, 2007|isbn=978-1-60010-111-3 |author1=Garner, Alex |author2=Wood, Ashley }}</ref> The game's novelization by [[Raymond Benson]] makes minor modifications to Raiden's history, except for the moment he receives Olga's sword, resulting in a change to his battle psyche. When Raiden kills Solidus he cuts the rope on [[Federal Hall National Memorial]]'s flagpole, causing an American flag to cover his enemy's body. This scene was deleted from the original game due to the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Metal Gear Solid 2: The Novel: Sons of Liberty |publisher=Del Rey |date=November 24, 2009 |isbn=978-0-345-50343-5 |author=Benson, Raymond |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/metalgearsolid200bens }}</ref>\n\nOutside the ''Metal Gear'' series, Raiden appears in the video game ''[[LittleBigPlanet (PlayStation 3)|LittleBigPlanet]]'' as a sticker and a playable sack-boy character in the ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' [[downloadable content]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/littlebigplanet/news/6202572/little-big-planet-update-metal-gear-solid-4-pack-impressions?sid=6202572&mode=previews|title=Little Big Planet Update: Metal Gear Solid 4 Pack Impressions|website=[[GameSpot]] |date=December 19, 2008|author=Torres, Ricardo |accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> He is an unlockable character in ''[[Evolution Skateboarding]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/sports/evolutionskateboarding/cheats.html?tag=tabs%253Bcheats|title=Evolution Skateboarding Hints & Cheats|website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> He also appears in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' as a collectible sticker and in ''[[Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood]]'' as an alternative skin for [[Ezio Auditore da Firenze]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/17/assassins-creed-brotherhood-play-as-raiden|title=Unlock Raiden in Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood|website=[[IGN]] |author=Ivan, Tom|date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Raiden is playable in the video games ''[[PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale]]'' and ''[[Super Bomberman R]]'' using his ''Metal Gear Rising'' design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-07-30-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-leak-outs-characters-stages |title=PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale leak outs characters, stages |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Phillips, Tom |date=July 30, 2012 |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801210326/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-07-30-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-leak-outs-characters-stages |archivedate=August 1, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vidaextra.com/accion/solid-snake-raiden-xavier-woods-muchos-personajes-se-unen-super-bomberman-r-su-nueva-actualizacion|title=Solid Snake, Raiden, Xavier Woods y muchos m\u00e1s personajes se unen a Super Bomberman R con su nueva actualizaci\u00f3n|date=27 June 2018|publisher=Vida Extra|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref> The [[webseries]] ''[[Mega64]]'' includes a parody of Raiden's story in ''Revengeance''; the character struggles against his darker persona while making breakfast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.platinumgames.com/games/metal-gear-rising-revengeance?age-verified=a08f2a98aa|title=History|publisher=Platinum Games|accessdate=December 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214070700/https://www.platinumgames.com/games/metal-gear-rising-revengeance?age-verified=a08f2a98aa|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Quote box |width = 26em |align = right |quote = \"Raiden was one of the most hated characters in gaming, mostly because he abruptly replaced Snake as the lead in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'', though it didnt help that he was prone to fits of whining. Even though he showed flashes of swordsmanship akin to the beloved Cyborg Ninja, fans rejected him with a passion. Perhaps thats why ''MGS'' creator Hideo Kojima decided to try and reform Raiden in the fans eyes, by going all the way with his Cyborg Ninja tribute. When Raiden burst back onto the stage in ''Metal Gear Solid 4'', he had transitioned into an unbeatable cyborg ninja. His unplayable appearances in ''MGS4'' won him so many new fans, he earned his rightful place as the star of his own game, ''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance''.\" |source = \u2014 GamesRadar <ref name=gr/>}}\n===Critical reaction===\nRaiden's replacement of fan favorite Solid Snake in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' proved controversial; [[GamesRadar]] considered the replacement a reason to dislike the series.<ref name=Radd>{{cite web|title='Controversial' Games: Dealing with Fan Backlash |date=November 10, 2009 |author=David Radd |publisher=Industry Gamers |url=http://www.industrygamers.com/galleries/controversial-games-dealing-with-fan-backlash/6/ |accessdate=2009-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118011716/http://www.industrygamers.com/galleries/controversial-games-dealing-with-fan-backlash/6 |archivedate=November 18, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=5 reasons to hate Metal Gear Solid |date=November 10, 2009|author=Reparaz, Mikel|publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/5-reasons-to-hate-metal-gear-solid/a-201104251739927009/g-20100610112655981027|accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> The same site criticized Raiden's role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' several times and called his inclusion one of the worst aspects of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shit characters who almost ruined their great games|author=Meikleham, Dave|publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/shit-characters-who-almost-ruined-their-great-games/a-20100325125657826031/g-2005120719070989166259|accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gaming's most bizarre decisions |date=December 10, 2009 |author=Meikleham, Dave |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/gamings-most-bizarre-decisions/a-2009121013514764096/g-2005120719070989166259/p-3 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322130140/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/gamings-most-bizarre-decisions/a-2009121013514764096/g-2005120719070989166259/p-3/ |archivedate=March 22, 2016 }}</ref> Snake's voice actor, [[David Hayter]], was also surprised by the inclusion of Raiden in ''Sons of Liberty'' believing his character was meant to be returning protagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalgearinformer.com/?p=13843|title=DAVID HAYTER ON HIS ROLE AS SNAKE: 'I TRIED TO DO SOMETHING VERY SPECIFIC WITH THIS CHARACTER'|website=Metal Gear Informer|date=6 April 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> In 2004, ''GameAxis Unwired'' published a fake interview in which Hideo Kojima expressed regret for creating the character.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Santos, Shoeless Wayne|date=September 2004|url=https://books.google.com/?id=G-kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT2&dq=The+News+That+Never+Was+GameAxis+Unwired+Raiden#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The News That Never Was|journal=GameAxis Unwired|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|issn=0219-872X|issue=|page=4|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> While calling ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' one of the biggest disappointments in video-game history, [[UGO Networks]]' Marissa Meli cited Raiden's debut as a key problem with the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trolled: The Biggest Disappointments in Video Games |publisher=UGO Networks |date=June 3, 2011 |author=Meli, Marissa |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/metal-gear-solid-2-2 |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611072134/http://www.ugo.com/games/metal-gear-solid-2-2 |archivedate=June 11, 2011 }}</ref> The book ''Playing with Videogames'' states that Raiden's inclusion was intended to surprise ''Metal Gear'' fans who, instead of playing as Snake, played as his opposite. Writer James Newman commented that fans' reactions were highly negative; they acted as though Kojima had betrayed their expectations. He compared Raiden to the controversial ''[[Star Wars]]'' character [[Jar Jar Binks]]. Newman considered trailers for ''Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater'' in which Raiden is mocked to be Konami's comic response to fans' disapproval.<ref name=\"playingwithvideogames\">{{cite book |title=Playing with Videogames |pages=39\u201340 |last=Newman |first=James |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-415-38523-7}}</ref> \n[[Eurogamer]]'s Tom Bramwell enjoyed Raiden's role, commenting that his interactions with the other characters also helped expand Solid Snake's character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 2 : Sons of Liberty - Review |website=Eurogamer |date=December 3, 2002 |author=Bramwell, Tom |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_mgs2_ps2 |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826060156/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_mgs2_ps2 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> Raiden's introduction was given an award for \"Biggest Surprise\" by [[GameSpot]] in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|title=Biggest Surprise |website=GameSpot |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/bestof_2001/p2_09.html |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008063452/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/bestof_2001/p2_09.html |archivedate=October 8, 2013 }}</ref> while Dave Meikleham from GamesRadar listed his appearance as one of the biggest plot twists in a video game because the trailers did not show him. Meikleham also called Raiden a \"surprisingly likeable character\" and found his dynamic with Solid Snake appealing.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 7 ... Games with mega plot twists you never saw coming |author=Meikleham, Dave |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/the-top-7-games-with-mega-plot-twists-you-never-saw-coming/a-2010111116427795018/g-2005120719070989166259/p-2 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404081240/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/f/the-top-7-games-with-mega-plot-twists-you-never-saw-coming/a-2010111116427795018/g-2005120719070989166259/p-2/ |archivedate=April 4, 2016 }}</ref> \n\nBefore joining [[Kojima Productions]], Ryan Payton stated that he was not disappointed by Raiden's introduction and liked the fact the ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' team kept his identity secret.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/interview-kojima-productions-ryan-payton?pager.offset=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019183937/http://www.1up.com/features/interview-kojima-productions-ryan-payton?pager.offset=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|title=Kojima Productions' Ryan Payton|author=Berghammer, Billy|website=1UP.com|accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref> Raiden's English voice actor [[Quinton Flynn]] was surprised by fans' response to the character but said it attracted new fans to the series. Flynn thought fans were angry at the idea that Raiden would replace Snake for all subsequent games.<ref name=\"gamingliberty\" /> Raiden's relationship with Rosemary was listed as the most awkward part of the ''Metal Gear'' series by [[1UP.com]], with writer Scott Sharkey speculating about Hideo Kojima's life because he said the relationship is autobiographical.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear's Top 5 Awkward Moments|website=1UP.com|date=June 3, 2011|author=Sharkey, Scott|url=http://www.1up.com/features/metal-gear-top-5-awkward|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019163635/http://www.1up.com/features/metal-gear-top-5-awkward|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 19, 2012|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref> '\n\nResponse to the character in subsequent games was mainly positive. ''GamePro''{{'}}s Pattrick Shaw analyzed his new design for ''Metal Gear Solid 4''; he said Raiden \"was in one hell of a fight\".<ref name=\"gamepro\"/> Raiden's redesign has been praised for reducing his androgynous appearance, thus making him more appealing.<ref>{{cite web |title=The complete history of Metal Gear |publisher=GamesRadar |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/the-complete-history-of-metal-gear/a-2010100413446869097/g-20100610112655981027/p-3 |accessdate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315210142/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/f/the-complete-history-of-metal-gear/a-2010100413446869097/g-20100610112655981027/p-3/ |archivedate=March 15, 2016 }}</ref> UGO placed Raiden's design in that game at 18th on its 2011 list of \"the most stylin' alternate costumes\",<ref>{{cite web |title=The Most Stylin' Alternate Costumes |publisher=UGO Networks |date=February 27, 2011 |author=Jensen, K. Thor |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/raiden-ezio |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304144503/http://www.ugo.com/games/raiden-ezio |archivedate=2011-03-04 }}</ref> but Gavin Mackenzie from ''PLAY'' listed it seventh on his list of inappropriate outfits, stating that the costume was \"cool\" but had unnecessary accessories.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 inappropriate outfits |publisher=Play |author=Mackenzie, Gavin |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-10-inappropriate-outfits/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503231627/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-10-inappropriate-outfits/ |archivedate=May 3, 2011 }}</ref> It has also been compared with [[Gray Fox (Metal Gear)|Gray Fox]]'s cybernetic-ninja design in ''[[Metal Gear Solid (1998 video game)|Metal Gear Solid]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top ten ninjas on PlayStation |publisher=Play |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-ten-ninjas-on-playstation/ |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313155314/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/features/top-ten-ninjas-on-playstation/ |archivedate=March 13, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Metal Gear Villains |website=IGN |author=Scheeden, Jeese |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/881/881015p8.html |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628231830/http://stars.ign.com/articles/881/881015p8.html |archivedate=June 28, 2012 }}</ref> GameSpot staff stated that Raiden \"is definitely the inheritor of the quasi-unkillable [[Cyborg Ninja]] inheritance\" when he made his first appearance in a ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' trailer. GameSpot applauded his actions in the trailer, calling it \"wordlessly awesome\" and comparing his stunts with those in the film ''[[Casshan: Robot Hunter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 06: Metal Gear Solid 4 Extended Trailer Impressions|website=GameSpot |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/metalgearsolid4/news/6149999/e3-06-metal-gear-solid-4-extended-trailer-impressions?mode=previews|date=May 10, 2006|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> Writers from Cheat Code Central referred to his fight against Vamp in another trailer as the \"undeniable highlight\" that would make player wish to use Raiden in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots Trailer Analysis |publisher=Cheat Code Central |url=http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/metalgearsolid4gunsofthepatriotstrailer2.html |author1=Beatty, D'Marcus |author2=Walker, Matthew |accessdate=August 8, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601150415/http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/metalgearsolid4gunsofthepatriotstrailer2.html |archivedate=June 1, 2012 }}</ref> \n\nDave Meikleham of GamesRadar wrote an article titled \"Why ''Metal Gear Solid: Rising'' [''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance''] will make you love Raiden\", writing that fans who disliked the character would find him appealing in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 09: Why Metal Gear Solid: Rising will make you love Raiden |publisher=GamesRadar|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/f/e3-09-why-metal-gear-solid-rising-will-make-you-love-raiden/a-2009060216521843009|author=Miekleham, Dave|accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> Raiden's role and development in ''Revengeance'' were found to be appealing, with GameSpot's Peter Brown praising his violent attitude that made him an outstanding anti-hero,<ref name=\"gspotreview\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=February 19, 2013 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review-6404028/ |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |website=GameSpot |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220060642/http://www.gamespot.com/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review-6404028/ |archive-date=2013-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> whereas [[GameTrailers]] wrote that Raiden contrasted with his ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' persona that was criticized in 2001.<ref name=\"gametrailers\">{{cite web |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/ux8c59/metal-gear-rising--revengeance-review |publisher=GameTrailers |date=February 19, 2013 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222053842/http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/ux8c59/metal-gear-rising--revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-22 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' said Raiden was now worthy of his own game based on his characterization.<ref name=\"Escapistreview\">{{cite web |last=Concepci\u00f3n |first=Miguel |date=February 19, 2013 |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/editorials/reviews/10193-Metal-Gear-Rising-Revengeance-Review-Outside-the-Box.2 |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance Review \u2013 Outside the Box |work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208103114/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/editorials/reviews/10193-Metal-Gear-Rising-Revengeance-Review-Outside-the-Box.2 |archive-date=2013-12-08 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Polygon'' said that while Raiden's actions provide a departure from the stealth games, his actions were referred as \"outlandish and ridiculous\". The detail given to Raiden's past was also praised.<ref name=\"polygon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/19/4002956/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review|title=''Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review: blood and thunder'' review|work=Polygon|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|accessdate=1 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421085839/http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/19/4002956/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review|archive-date=2015-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> IGN wrote that fans of ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' would enjoy the game more because Raiden can replicate his moves from that game's cutscenes in gameplay.<ref name=\"IGNreview\">{{cite web |last=Dyer |first=Mitch |date=February 18, 2013 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/19/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |website=IGN |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221133025/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/19/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Eurogamer said a major change in Raiden's characterization is ''Revengeance'', referring to him as a \"the ultimate cyborg and also the ultimate killer\" based on his darker persona that is explored in combat.<ref name=\"eurogamerreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-02-19-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |website=[[Eurogamer]] |title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance review |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=February 20, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219111713/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-02-19-metal-gear-rising-revengeance-review |archive-date=2013-02-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The idea of Raiden primarily using his sword to counterattack firepower was found appealing by ''Complex'' due to how ''Revengeance'' explores the soldier as a melee fighter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/02/10-things-you-should-know-about-metal-gear-rising-revengeance/no-guns|title=10 Things You Should Know About Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance|website=Complex|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Flynn's performance earned mixed response due to the tones he gives Raiden when interacting with allies and enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cgmagonline.com/reviews/metal-gear-rising-revengeance/|title=METAL GEAR RISING: REVENGEANCE (XBOX 360) REVIEW|website=CGMagonline|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"eurogamerreview\"/>\n\n===Popularity===\n[[File:Metal Gear Rising promotion art.jpg|thumb|upright|Raiden's artwork used as a promotional piece in Leeds, UK, for ''Revengeance''.]]\n''[[Play (UK magazine)|PLAY]]'' editor Nick Jones listed the scene in which Raiden is nude as his fourth-favorite moment of the franchise, calling it the \"one of the funniest moments in gaming history\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid \u2013 My Top Five Moments |publisher=Play |author=Jones, Nick |url=http://www.play-mag.co.uk/editors-blog/metal-gear-solid-%e2%80%93-my-top-five-moments/ |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928184333/http://www.play-mag.co.uk/editors-blog/metal-gear-solid-%E2%80%93-my-top-five-moments/ |archivedate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref> Lisa Foiles of ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' included him on her 2014 list of top five katana wielders, writing \"this is not a popularity contest and Raiden qualifies\" even in ''MGS2'' where \"he was whiny, an emo, and kind of a bitch\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Top 5 Katana Wielders |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/9182-Top-5-Katana-Wielders |title=Top 5 Katana Wielders &#124; Top 5 with Lisa Foiles Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist |publisher=Escapistmagazine.com |accessdate=2014-06-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523220120/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/9182-Top-5-Katana-Wielders |archivedate=2014-05-23 }}</ref> Raiden proved to be more popular in Japan; according to [[Yoji Shinkawa]] this was because he matched the stereotype of the [[manga]] hero.<ref>{{cite web|title=The art of Metal Gear: Yoji Shinkawa's visual legacy |website=VG247 |date=April 24, 2013 |author=Cook, Dave |url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/04/23/the-art-of-metal-gear-yoji-shinkawas-visual-legacy/ |accessdate=April 26, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426004119/http://www.vg247.com/2013/04/23/the-art-of-metal-gear-yoji-shinkawas-visual-legacy/ |archivedate=April 26, 2013 }}</ref> \n\n''[[Game Informer]]'' placed him on \"The Snubbed List\" of the best characters of the 2000s in response to his new design because it made fans like the idea of a new ''Metal Gear'' game solely focused on Raiden.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Snubbed List |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2010/11/19/the-snubbed-list.aspx |magazine=Game Informer |author=Bertz, Matt |date=November 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210154112/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2010/11/19/the-snubbed-list.aspx |archivedate=February 10, 2011 }}</ref>  In a 2010 ''[[Famitsu]]'' readers' poll, Raiden was voted the 42nd most-popular video game character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3177896 |title=Snake Beats Mario, Is Coolest Video Game Character Ever |author=Glifford, Kevin |website=[[1UP.com]] |accessdate=March 10, 2010 |date=February 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307232332/http://www.1up.com/do/newsstory?cid=3177896 |archivedate=March 7, 2016 }}</ref> ''[[GamePro]]'' called Raiden's encounter with Vamp in this game one of the \"most memorable cinematics\" of the series because of his change of fighting style from his debut as he \"redeems his girlish image\",<ref name=\"gamepro\">{{cite magazine|title=Feature: Metal Gear Solid Rising: 6 Things to Expect from the Game |magazine=GamePro|date=June 11, 2009 |author=Shaw, Pattrick|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/210813/metal-gear-solid-rising-6-things-to-expect-from-the-game/|accessdate=June 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628070625/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/210813/metal-gear-solid-rising-6-things-to-expect-from-the-game/|archivedate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> while [[IGN]] listed it as the 80th best moment in video-game history for similar reasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Video Game Moments |website=IGN |url=http://www.ign.com/top/video-game-moments/89 |accessdate=March 2, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303000639/http://www.ign.com/top/video-game-moments/89 |archivedate=March 3, 2012 }}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' ranked Raiden as the 12th-greatest soldier in video games, \"even as he's not as cool as Solid Snake\",<ref>\nChad Hunter, Michael Rougeau, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/05/the-50-greatest-soldiers-in-video-games/raiden The 50 Greatest Soldiers In Video Games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106064739/http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/05/the-50-greatest-soldiers-in-video-games/raiden |date=2013-11-06 }} , Complex.com, May 25, 2013.</ref> while GamesRadar called ''Revengeance'' \"perhaps the greatest cyborg ninja game of all time\".<ref name=gr>{{cite web|author=Henry Gilbert |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/deadliest-cyborg-ninjas-gaming-history/ |title=The deadliest cyborg ninjas in gaming history |publisher=GamesRadar |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007212618/http://www.gamesradar.com/deadliest-cyborg-ninjas-gaming-history/ |archivedate=2013-10-07 }}</ref> ''[[Play (UK magazine)|PLAY]]'' ranked Raiden as the second-top ninja in games.<ref name=play>''PLAY'' 232, page 34.</ref> While surpassed by Solid Snake, GamesRadar listed Raiden as the second-best video game hero of all time.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-video-game-heroes/|title=2. Raiden (Metal Gear)|publisher=GamesRadar|accessdate=September 22, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121205033358/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-video-game-heroes/|archive-date=2012-12-05|url-status=live}}\n</ref> In 2012, [[manga artist]] [[Hiro Mashima]] drew an illustration of Raiden in anticipation of the series' following games. He mentioned having had difficulties illustrating the character.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 09: Why Metal Gear Solid: Rising will make you love Raiden |publisher=Siliconera |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2012/09/04/fairy-tail-artist-is-excited-by-metal-gear-solid-news-draws-raiden/ |date=September 4, 2012 |accessdate=September 6, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907155342/http://www.siliconera.com/2012/09/04/fairy-tail-artist-is-excited-by-metal-gear-solid-news-draws-raiden/ |archivedate=September 7, 2012 }}</ref> Following ''Metal Gear Solid 4''{{'}}s release, Raiden also appeared in more lists. IGN's Jesse Schedeen listed Raiden as one of the \"gaming icons\" and [[most valuable player]]s of 2009, in response to his role in an upcoming ''Metal Gear'' title.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Cast of Characters: GDC '09 |website=IGN |date=March 30, 2009 |author=Schedeen, Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/967/967836p2.html |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204221908/http://stars.ign.com/articles/967/967836p2.html |archivedate=December 4, 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The MVP's of E3 2009 |website=IGN |author=Schedeen, Jesse |url=http://stars.ign.com/articles/992/992651p3.html |accessdate=June 30, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204065533/http://stars.ign.com/articles/992/992651p3.html |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref> [[Den of Geek]] listed Raiden as one of the most sexually appealing video game characters, calling him disappointing to some but to others \"a pin-up forever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/games/11632/top-10-sexiest-computer-game-characters |title=Top 10 sexiest computer game characters|author=Haigh, Matthew |publisher=Den of Geek|date=July 31, 2008|accessdate=August 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616015341/http://www.denofgeek.com/games/11632/top-10-sexiest-computer-game-characters|archive-date=2012-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn promoting ''Revengeance'', Raiden's design by Shinkawa was used in presence in London, Leeds and Liverpool during 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.endoftheline.co/metal-gear-rising-revengeance-mural/|title=METAL GEAR RISING : REVENGEANCE MURAL|website=End of the Line|date=12 February 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Voice actor [[Reuben Langdon]] described Raiden as a character he always wanted to play as most notably on ''Super Smash Bros''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meristation.as.com/zonaforo/topic/2207133/|title=Reuben Langdon (doblador Raiden) \"confiesa\" haber doblado a \u00e9ste en Super Smash Bros|website=Meristation|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Analysis===\nRaiden's role in ''Metal Gear Solid 2'' has been analyzed by several writers, who said he is intended to represent the player.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=87|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David }}</ref> Early in the game, when Raiden's [[virtual reality]] training is mentioned, the game shows scenes from the previous game ''[[Metal Gear Solid (1998 video game)|Metal Gear Solid]]'' in which the player takes control of Solid Snake.<ref>{{cite book|title=Joystick soldiers: the politics of play in military video games|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RTPmwwL63iwC&pg=PA263&dq=Raiden+Metal+Gear#v=onepage&q=Raiden%20Metal%20Gear&f=false|pages=263\u2013264|publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=August 8, 2009|isbn=978-0-415-99660-0|author=Huntemann, Nina B.}}</ref> Raiden's interactions with veteran Solid Snake identify the former as \"a ''Metal Gear'' fan\". As the game progresses it is stated that Raiden \"has become Snake\", having developed skills similar to those he gained from taking part in the Big Shell's fights that resemble ''Metal Gear Solid''{{'}}s Shadow Moses Island.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=87\u201388|publisher=Lexington Books|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David}}</ref> The recurring plot twist involving Raiden's life and the people with whom he often interacts have been praised as being early post-truth content in a video game. Raiden's interaction with the Patriots was also analyzing the way the digital era became relevant over a decade after ''Sons of Liberty'' was released.<ref name=\"glixel\">{{cite web |author=Wiltshire, Alex|url=http://www.glixel.com/news/how-metal-gear-solid-2-foretold-our-post-truth-future-w450225 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119172715/http://www.glixel.com/news/how-metal-gear-solid-2-foretold-our-post-truth-future-w450225 |title=Flashback: How 'Metal Gear Solid 2' Foretold Our Post-Truth Future |archive-date=19 November 2016 |website=Glixel |url-status=dead |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>https://nowloading.co/posts/4199069/amp</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/the-scary-political-relevance-of-metal-gear-solid-2 |title=The Scary Political Relevance of 'Metal Gear Solid 2' |author=Kunzelman, Cameron |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=2018-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223120038/https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/the-scary-political-relevance-of-metal-gear-solid-2 |archive-date=2017-02-23 |url-status=live}}</ref> Raiden's development in ''Sons of Liberty'' were becomes a stronger soldier for imitating Snake's role in ''Metal Gear Solid'' was retold in ''The Phantom Pain'' when the player learns their character, [[Venom Snake]], is not the famous Big Boss but instead a doctor who was hypnotized into being a double of the mercenary across the video game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://webnewtype.com/special/metalgear/en_01/|title=Manabu Makime & Hitori Nojima Metal Gear discussion vol.1|website=Newtype|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLater in the game, a character tells Raiden to \"turn off the console\", which confuses both Raiden and the player; this was first interpreted as a [[fourth wall]]-breaking joke but the game's climax goes deeper into Raiden's connection with the player.<ref name=\"avatarsofstory\"/> When his superiors force Raiden to kill the game's antagonist, Solidus Snake, the designers tell the player to finish the game.<ref name=Weise>{{cite web|title=How Videogames Express Ideas |author=Matthew Weise |work=Level Up: Digital Games Research Conference |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |year=2003 |url=http://www.digra.org/dl/db/05150.07598.pdf |accessdate=November 21, 2009 |page=13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415123434/http://www.digra.org/dl/db/05150.07598.pdf |archivedate=April 15, 2010 }}</ref> Both the player and Raiden take different paths at the game's end; the player is told not to waste time playing games<ref name=\"avatarsofstory\">{{cite book|title=Avatars of story|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dzX3n66QRiEC&pg=PA225&dq=Raiden+Metal+Gear#v=onepage&q=Raiden%20Metal%20Gear&f=false|page=225|publisher=[[University Of Minnesota Press]]|author=Ryan, Marie-Laure|isbn=978-0-8166-4686-9}}</ref> while Raiden's character is expanded with his decision to move on with his life, rejecting his previous identity by discarding the [[dog tag]]s the player wore in the beginning.<ref>{{cite book|title=Utopic Dreams and Apocalyptic Fantasies: Critical Approaches to Researching Video Game Play|url=https://books.google.com/?id=drH7l-VYUGEC&pg=PA73&dq=raiden+metal+gear#v=onepage&q=raiden%20metal%20gear&f=false|pages=89|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|date=September 25, 2010|isbn=978-0-7391-4700-9 |author=Emmbrick, David }}</ref> \n\nUpon the revelation of Raiden's new design as a cyborg ninja, writers said he distanced himself from his previous appearance that imitated Solid Snake.<ref name=\"playingwithvideogames\"/> Raiden's increasingly masculine redesigns following his debut were noted be a leaning to Western heroes in gaming despite Raiden retaining his original characterization by Todd Harper in the book ''Queerness in Play''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Queerness in Play|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2018|isbn=978-3319905419|page=152|author=Harper, Todd}}</ref> IGN also said Raiden becomes a different type of game hero with a new, direct fighting style.<ref name=\"gamepro\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.ign.com/articles/121/1214596p1.html |title=Opinion: Revengeance Will Ruin Metal Gear Solid |website=IGN |author=George, Richards |date=December 12, 2011 |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122062359/http://games.ign.com/articles/121/1214596p1.html |archivedate=January 22, 2012 }}</ref> being instead compared with the lead characters from ''[[Devil May Cry]]'' and ''[[God of War (franchise)|God of War]]''  favorably due to how they fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/stop-your-delusional-whining-platinums-metal-gear-rising-best-thing-could-have-happened/ |title=Stop your delusional whining: Platinum's Metal Gear Rising is the best thing that could have happened |publisher=GamesRadar |author=Houghton, David |date=December 13, 2011 |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220031736/http://www.gamesradar.com/stop-your-delusional-whining-platinums-metal-gear-rising-best-thing-could-have-happened/ |archivedate=February 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/meristation/2012/12/11/avances/1355245200_111196.html|title=Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance, Impresiones|website=Meristation|date=2 July 2017|accessdate=April 5, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Metal Gear characters|List of ''Metal Gear'' characters]]\n*[[Ninja in popular culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/originals/catching-up-to-metal-gear-rising-raiden-s-story-so-far|title=Catching up to Metal Gear Rising: Raiden's story so far\n|publisher=GameZone|date=February 3, 2013|author=Faciane, Alex}}\n{{portal bar|Japan|Speculative fiction|Video games}}\n{{Metal Gear}}\n\n[[Category:Adoptee characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Hideo Kojima]]\n[[Category:Characters designed by Yoji Shinkawa]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Cyborg characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]] <!--Even if he's not actually black, he was still born in Liberia/Africa.-->\n[[Category:Fictional characters with multiple personalities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n[[Category:Fictional child soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Army Delta Force personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional First Liberian Civil War veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional immigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Fictional Liberian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional private military members]]\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional super soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Konami protagonists]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional mercenaries in video games]]\n[[Category:Metal Gear characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional military personnel in video games]]\n[[Category:Ninja characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional secret agents and spies in video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale fighters]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with electric or magnetic abilities]]\n", "name_user": "Tintor2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMain games", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raiden_(Metal_Gear)"}
{"title_page": "Zo\u00eb Jenny", "text_new": "'''Zo\u00eb Jenny''' (born 16 March 1974 in [[Basel]], Switzerland) is a [[List of Swiss people#Writers|Swiss writer]]. Her first novel, ''[[The Pollen Room]]'', was published in German in 1997 and has been translated into 27 languages. Since 2003 she has been living in [[London]]. In 2008, she married Matthew Homfray, a British [[veterinary surgeon]] and pharmaceuticals consultant. Her newest novel, ''The Sky is Changing'', was her first written in English and was published by [[Legend Press]] in June 2010 [http://www.new-books-in-german.com/english/650/253/253/129002/design1.html]. She was awarded the [[Aspekte-Literaturpreis]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Das Bl\u00fctenstaubzimmer'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 1997 (''The Pollen Room'', New York 1999)\n*''Der Ruf des Muschelhorns'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 2000\n*''Mittelp\u00fcnktchens Reise um die Welt'' (illustrated children's book), M\u00fcnchen 2001\n*''Ein schnelles Leben'' (novel), Berlin 2002\n*''Das Portrait'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 2007\n*''The Sky is Changing'' (novel), Legend Press 2010\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Helveticat}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jenny, Zoe}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swiss novelists]]\n[[Category:German-language writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Zo\u00eb Jenny''' (born 16 March 1974 in [[Basel]], Switzerland) is a [[List of Swiss people#Writers|Swiss writer]]. Her first novel, ''[[The Pollen Room]]'', was published in German in 1997 and has been translated into 27 languages. Since 2003 she has been living in [[London]]. In 2008, she married Matthew Homfray, a British [[veterinary surgeon]] and pharmaceuticals consultant. Her newest novel, ''The Sky is Changing'', was her first written in English and was published by [[Legend Press]] in June 2010 [http://www.new-books-in-german.com/english/650/253/253/129002/design1.html]. She was awarded the [[Aspekte-Literaturpreis]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Das Bl\u00fctenstaubzimmer'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 1997 (''The Pollen Room'', New York 1999)\n*''Der Ruf des Muschelhorns'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 2000\n*''Mittelp\u00fcnktchens Reise um die Welt'' (illustrated children's book), M\u00fcnchen 2001\n*''Ein schnelles Leben'' (novel), Berlin 2002\n*''Das Portrait'' (novel), Frankfurt am Main 2007\n*''The Sky is Changing'' (novel), Legend Press 2010\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Helveticat}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jenny, Zoe}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swiss novelists]]\n[[Category:German-language writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zo%C3%AB_Jenny"}
{"title_page": "Wendy Benchley", "text_new": "[[File:WendyBenchley Wiki Only Photo.jpg|thumb]]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Wendy Benchley\n| image              =\n| alt                = Photo of Wendy Benchley, seated and facing forward\n| caption            = Benchley in 2019\n| birth_name         = Winifred Wesson\n| birth_date         = {{bda|1941|02|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Montclair, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Ocean conservationist, environmental activist, former councilwoman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Peter Benchley]]|1964|2006|reason=died}}\n\n{{marriage|John Jeppson III|2011}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n\n'''Winifred''' \"'''Wendy'''\" '''Benchley''' ({{n\u00e9e}} '''Wesson'''; born February 4, 1941) is a marine and environmental conservation advocate and former councilwoman from New Jersey. She is known for co-founding various environmental organizations and for being the wife of author [[Peter Benchley]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nWendy Wesson was born and raised in [[Montclair, New Jersey]] to Harrison and Dorcas Wesson. Harrison Wesson was a surgeon and served in the Philippines during WWII. Wendy Wesson graduated from [[Montclair High School (New Jersey)|Montclair High School]] in 1959, after which she did a grand tour of Europe with her family. Wesson continued her studies at [[Skidmore College]] where she majored in philosophy and psychology.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=After Nine Years on Borough Council, Wendy Benchley Sets New Agenda |last=Stratton |first=Jean|url=http://www.towntopics.com/apr0208/stratton.php|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> While in college, Benchley became involved in activism and was arrested for picketing [[F. W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth]] in Saratoga Springs in protest of the department store's segregation policy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWendy Wesson met Peter Benchley at the Jared Coffin House in Nantucket in 1963, and the two were married the following year. The couple had their first child, a daughter named Tracy, in 1967.<ref>{{cite book |last=Eilperin |first=Juliet |date=2011 |title=Demon Fish: Travels Through the Hidden World of Sharks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmrQe3ty5koC&lpg=PA45&ots=9UZefpKolU&dq=wendy%20benchley%20tv%20appearances&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=wendy%20benchley%20tv%20appearances&f=false|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group |page=46 |isbn=0307379795}}</ref> They later had a son named Clayton in 1969, and a third child, Christopher, in 1987.\n\n==Political and environmental activism==\nWhile in [[Pennington, New Jersey]], Peter Benchley wrote the novel [[Jaws (novel)|''Jaws'']], which became a critical and commercial success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scene4.com/archivesqv6/2014/nov-2014/1114/patrickwalsh1114.html|title=PETER BENCHLEY Patrick Walsh Scene4 Magazine November 2014|website=www.scene4.com|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> The process of researching \u2018Jaws\u2019 and the aftermath of the novel\u2019s success and film adaptation left both Peter and Wendy Benchley with a profound interest in sharks and ocean conservation. The couple subsequently became involved in conservation efforts and traveled internationally to meet with researchers and go [[Shark cage diving|cage diving]] with sharks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sharks on Cape Cod: Just how scared should we be? |last =Swiden |first=Neil|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2019/07/09/sharks-cape-just-how-scared-should/ozDKUj8vEfeFd00BeSGpHJ/story.html|date=July 9, 2019 |accessdate=October 19, 2019 |work=Boston Globe}}</ref> Benchley served as a Board member of the [[Environmental Defense Fund]] (EDF) from 1986 to 2006<ref>{{cite web |title=Great White Sharks: From Terror of the Seas to Admired Creatures|url=https://guardianlv.com/2014/07/great-white-sharks-from-terror-of-the-seas-to-admired-creatures/|date=July 31, 2015 |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> and Peter was an EDF spokesperson. They made appearances together to speak about protecting sharks and conservation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenworkingforoceans.org/2014/10/jaws-a-family-movie-a-teaching-moment/|title=Jaws: A Family Movie, a Teaching Moment|last=ecurren|website=Women Working for Oceans|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> Peter Benchley recalled his wife saving his life in 1974 during a televised cage diving expedition in the [[Neptune Islands]] off of Australia. Unnoticed by the crew, the [[great white shark]] being filmed got its teeth entangled in the rope that Peter Benchley\u2019s cage was suspended by and was struggling to break free. Wendy was the only one on-board the crew\u2019s boat to notice and she successfully attempted to free the rope from the shark\u2019s mouth before it was severed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Benchley |first=Peter |date=2003 |title=Shark Trouble: True Stories About Sharks and the Sea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7r6SDwAAQBAJ&ppis=_c&lpg=PP1&dq=Shark%20Trouble%3A%20True%20Stories%20About%20Sharks%20and%20the%20Sea&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=wendy&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=45 |isbn=0385901356}}</ref>\n\nWendy Benchley later became active in environmentalism and grassroots political causes outside of marine conservation, co-founding the New Jersey Environmental Federation and becoming involved in New Jersey politics. During this time she advocated for green energy and environmental reforms.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=August 9, 2012 |title=Wendy Benchley on MVTV's William Waterway Interview |language=English |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j_YWay1xOr0 |access-date=October 21, 2019 }}</ref> Wendy was elected to the Mercer County Board of Chosen Freeholders in 1992, before being elected to the [[Borough of Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton Borough]] Council for three terms, from 1999 to 2008 before leaving New Jersey politics to focus on ocean conservation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wendy W. Benchley|url=http://www.sharksavers.org/!trash/leadership/board-of-directors/wendy-benchley/|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u2013present===\nPeter Benchley died of pulmonary fibrosis on February 11, 2006 at the couple's home in [[Princeton, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/13/books/peter-benchley-author-of-jaws-dies-at-65.htmloscar |title=Peter Benchley, Author of 'Jaws,' Dies at 65|last =Wyatt |first=Edward |date=February 13, 2006 |website =New York Times|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> Wendy Benchley, along with [[David Helvarg]], co-founded the [[Peter Benchley Ocean Awards]] in 2008 to honor the memory of the late Peter Benchley. Referred to as \u201cthe Academy Awards of the ocean\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url =https://narratively.com/how-the-creator-of-jaws-became-the-sharks-greatest-defender/oscar |title=How the Creator of \u2018Jaws\u2019 Became the Shark\u2019s Greatest Defender|last=Dowling |first=David |date=August 15, 2014 |website=Narratively|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>, the Peter Benchley Ocean Awards recognize outstanding achievements in the area of ocean conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.news.ucsb.edu/2016/016310/winning-ocean-oscar |title= Winning the Ocean Oscar |last =Badham |first=James |date=January 12, 2016 |website=The Current|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> The awards were originally a project of [[Blue Frontier]] but they later became a separate organization headed by Benchley and Helvarg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bluefront.org/projects/the-peter-benchley-ocean-awards/|title=The Peter Benchley Ocean Awards|website=Blue Frontier Campaign|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> In addition to taking part in hosting and nominating recipients of the Peter Benchley Ocean Awards, Benchley has continued to advocate for marine conservation in other arenas. Benchley is an advisory trustee of the EDF, president of the board of SharkSavers, and a boardmember of [[WildAid]] and [[Blue Frontier Campaign]]. Benchley helped to facilitate the merger between SharkSavers and WildAid in 2014, which saw both organizations focus their resources on campaigns against [[sharkfin soup]] consumption, a leading cause of sharkfishing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parvatimagazine.com/2018/04/maps-wendy-benchley-ocean-advocate/|title=Wendy Benchley is a Passionate Ocean Advocate and MAPS Supporter|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/shark-savers-joins-wildaid/|title=Shark Savers Joins WildAid|access-date=October 19, 2019|date=March 10, 2014 |website=WildAid}}</ref> \n\nBenchley has supported organizations such as the Aspen Institute High Seas Initiative and the The Coral Reefs on the High Seas Initiative to implement new marine conservation policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://peterbenchleyoceanawards.org/about/cofounders|title=Co-founders, Wendy Benchley|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> Benchley supported BiteBack's advocacy against irresponsible media coverage of sharks and the sale of shark products such as sharkfin soup and shark steaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deeperblue.com/british-tv-celebrities-among-the-latest-to-call-for-responsible-shark-journalism/|title=British TV Celebrities Among The Latest To Call For Responsible Shark Journalism |last=Liang |first=John |date=August 16, 2018 |website=Narratively|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> In 2011, Benchley married John Jepson III, the grandson of industrialist [[John Jeppson]].\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nBenchley was awarded the 2014 [[International SeaKeepers Society#The SeaKeeper Award|SeaKeeper Award]], and was inducted into the Women Diver\u2019s Hall of Fame in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridadiver.net/women-divers-hall-of-fame-inducts-new-members2015/ |title=Women Divers Hall of Fame Inducts Six New Members for 2015 |date=March 24, 2015 |website=Florida Diver|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>  Benchley received the 2016 Beneath the Sea, Diver of the Year Award for environmentalism<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beneaththesea.org/divers-of-the-year/divers-of-the-year-2016/62746 |title=Beneath the Sea proudly presents \u2026The Class of 2016: Divers of the Year|website=beneaththesea.org|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> and 2017 Pegasus Wings Awards for her lifetime achievements as an ocean conservationist. In 2019 she was awarded the Rob Stewart Foundation Lifetime Achievement for Ocean Conservation Award.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pegasusfoundation.org/2017-pegasus-wings-awards/ |title=2017 PEGASUS WINGS AWARDS|website=Pegasus Foundation|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|-\n|2007\n|''The Shark Is Still Working: The Impact & Legacy of 'Jaws'''\n|Participant\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2007\n|''Diving Into 'Blue Water, White Death'''\n|Participant\n|Video documentary\n|-\n|2010\n|''Jaws: The Inside Story''\n|Herself\n|TV documentary\n|-\n|2012\n|''How \u2018Jaws\u2019 Changed the World''\n|Herself\n|TV documentary\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Work\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Nova (American TV program)|Nova]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"Why Sharks Attack\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2400254}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benchley, Wendy}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:Montclair High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:New Jersey city council members]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Pennington, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Skidmore College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Wendy Benchley\n| image              =\n| alt                = Photo of Wendy Benchley, seated and facing forward\n| caption            = Benchley in 2019\n| birth_name         = Winifred Wesson\n| birth_date         = {{bda|1941|02|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Montclair, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Ocean conservationist, environmental activist, former councilwoman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Peter Benchley]]|1964|2006|reason=died}}\n\n{{marriage|John Jeppson III|2011}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n\n'''Winifred''' \"'''Wendy'''\" '''Benchley''' ({{n\u00e9e}} '''Wesson'''; born February 4, 1941) is a marine and environmental conservation advocate and former councilwoman from New Jersey. She is known for co-founding various environmental organizations and for being the wife of author [[Peter Benchley]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nWendy Wesson was born and raised in [[Montclair, New Jersey]] to Harrison and Dorcas Wesson. Harrison Wesson was a surgeon and served in the Philippines during WWII. Wendy Wesson graduated from [[Montclair High School (New Jersey)|Montclair High School]] in 1959, after which she did a grand tour of Europe with her family. Wesson continued her studies at [[Skidmore College]] where she majored in philosophy and psychology.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=After Nine Years on Borough Council, Wendy Benchley Sets New Agenda |last=Stratton |first=Jean|url=http://www.towntopics.com/apr0208/stratton.php|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> While in college, Benchley became involved in activism and was arrested for picketing [[F. W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth]] in Saratoga Springs in protest of the department store's segregation policy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWendy Wesson met Peter Benchley at the Jared Coffin House in Nantucket in 1963, and the two were married the following year. The couple had their first child, a daughter named Tracy, in 1967.<ref>{{cite book |last=Eilperin |first=Juliet |date=2011 |title=Demon Fish: Travels Through the Hidden World of Sharks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmrQe3ty5koC&lpg=PA45&ots=9UZefpKolU&dq=wendy%20benchley%20tv%20appearances&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=wendy%20benchley%20tv%20appearances&f=false|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group |page=46 |isbn=0307379795}}</ref> They later had a son named Clayton in 1969, and a third child, Christopher, in 1987.\n\n==Political and environmental activism==\nWhile in [[Pennington, New Jersey]], Peter Benchley wrote the novel [[Jaws (novel)|''Jaws'']], which became a critical and commercial success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scene4.com/archivesqv6/2014/nov-2014/1114/patrickwalsh1114.html|title=PETER BENCHLEY Patrick Walsh Scene4 Magazine November 2014|website=www.scene4.com|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> The process of researching \u2018Jaws\u2019 and the aftermath of the novel\u2019s success and film adaptation left Peter Benchley with a profound interest in sharks and ocean conservation. The couple subsequently became involved in conservation efforts and traveled internationally to meet with researchers and go [[Shark cage diving|cage diving]] with sharks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sharks on Cape Cod: Just how scared should we be? |last =Swiden |first=Neil|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2019/07/09/sharks-cape-just-how-scared-should/ozDKUj8vEfeFd00BeSGpHJ/story.html|date=July 9, 2019 |accessdate=October 19, 2019 |work=Boston Globe}}</ref> Benchley served as a Board member of the [[Environmental Defense Fund]] (EDF) from 1986 to 2006<ref>{{cite web |title=Great White Sharks: From Terror of the Seas to Admired Creatures|url=https://guardianlv.com/2014/07/great-white-sharks-from-terror-of-the-seas-to-admired-creatures/|date=July 31, 2015 |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> and Peter was an EDF spokesperson. They made appearances together to speak about protecting sharks and conservation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenworkingforoceans.org/2014/10/jaws-a-family-movie-a-teaching-moment/|title=Jaws: A Family Movie, a Teaching Moment|last=ecurren|website=Women Working for Oceans|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> Peter Benchley recalled his wife saving his life in 1974 during a televised cage diving expedition in the [[Neptune Islands]] off of Australia. Unnoticed by the crew, the [[great white shark]] being filmed got its teeth entangled in the rope that Peter Benchley\u2019s cage was suspended by and was struggling to break free. Wendy was the only one on-board the crew\u2019s boat to notice and she successfully attempted to free the rope from the shark\u2019s mouth before it was severed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Benchley |first=Peter |date=2003 |title=Shark Trouble: True Stories About Sharks and the Sea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7r6SDwAAQBAJ&ppis=_c&lpg=PP1&dq=Shark%20Trouble%3A%20True%20Stories%20About%20Sharks%20and%20the%20Sea&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=wendy&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=45 |isbn=0385901356}}</ref>\n\nBenchley later became active in environmentalism and grassroots political causes outside of marine conservation, co-founding the New Jersey Environmental Federation and becoming involved in New Jersey politics. During this time Benchley advocated for green energy and environmental reforms.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=August 9, 2012 |title=Wendy Benchley on MVTV's William Waterway Interview |language=English |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j_YWay1xOr0 |access-date=October 21, 2019 }}</ref> Wendy was elected to the Mercer County Board of Chosen Freeholders in 1992, before being elected to the [[Borough of Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton Borough]] Council for three terms, from 1999 to 2008 before leaving New Jersey politics to focus on ocean conservation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wendy W. Benchley|url=http://www.sharksavers.org/!trash/leadership/board-of-directors/wendy-benchley/|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u2013present===\nPeter Benchley died of pulmonary fibrosis on February 11, 2006 at the couple's home in [[Princeton, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/13/books/peter-benchley-author-of-jaws-dies-at-65.htmloscar |title=Peter Benchley, Author of 'Jaws,' Dies at 65|last =Wyatt |first=Edward |date=February 13, 2006 |website =New York Times|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> Benchley, along with [[David Helvarg]], co-founded the [[Peter Benchley Ocean Awards]] in 2008 to honor the memory of the late Peter Benchley. Referred to as \u201cthe Academy Awards of the ocean\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url =https://narratively.com/how-the-creator-of-jaws-became-the-sharks-greatest-defender/oscar |title=How the Creator of \u2018Jaws\u2019 Became the Shark\u2019s Greatest Defender|last=Dowling |first=David |date=August 15, 2014 |website=Narratively|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>, the Peter Benchley Ocean Awards recognize outstanding achievements in the area of ocean conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.news.ucsb.edu/2016/016310/winning-ocean-oscar |title= Winning the Ocean Oscar |last =Badham |first=James |date=January 12, 2016 |website=The Current|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> The awards were originally a project of [[Blue Frontier]] but they later became a separate organization headed by Benchley and Helvarg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bluefront.org/projects/the-peter-benchley-ocean-awards/|title=The Peter Benchley Ocean Awards|website=Blue Frontier Campaign|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> In addition to taking part in hosting and nominating recipients of the Peter Benchley Ocean Awards, Benchley has continued to advocate for marine conservation in other arenas. Benchley is an advisory trustee of the EDF, president of the board of SharkSavers, and a boardmember of [[WildAid]] and [[Blue Frontier Campaign]]. Benchley helped to facilitate the merger between SharkSavers and WildAid in 2014, which saw both organizations focus their resources on campaigns against [[sharkfin soup]] consumption, a leading cause of sharkfishing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parvatimagazine.com/2018/04/maps-wendy-benchley-ocean-advocate/|title=Wendy Benchley is a Passionate Ocean Advocate and MAPS Supporter|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/shark-savers-joins-wildaid/|title=Shark Savers Joins WildAid|access-date=October 19, 2019|date=March 10, 2014 |website=WildAid}}</ref> \n\nBenchley has supported organizations such as the Aspen Institute High Seas Initiative and the The Coral Reefs on the High Seas Initiative to implement new marine conservation policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://peterbenchleyoceanawards.org/about/cofounders|title=Co-founders, Wendy Benchley|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> Benchley supported BiteBack's advocacy against irresponsible media coverage of sharks and the sale of shark products such as sharkfin soup and shark steaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deeperblue.com/british-tv-celebrities-among-the-latest-to-call-for-responsible-shark-journalism/|title=British TV Celebrities Among The Latest To Call For Responsible Shark Journalism |last=Liang |first=John |date=August 16, 2018 |website=Narratively|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> In 2011, Benchley married John Jepson III, the grandson of industrialist [[John Jeppson]].\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nBenchley was awarded the 2014 [[International SeaKeepers Society#The SeaKeeper Award|SeaKeeper Award]], and was inducted into the Women Diver\u2019s Hall of Fame in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridadiver.net/women-divers-hall-of-fame-inducts-new-members2015/ |title=Women Divers Hall of Fame Inducts Six New Members for 2015 |date=March 24, 2015 |website=Florida Diver|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>  Benchley received the 2016 Beneath the Sea, Diver of the Year Award for environmentalism<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beneaththesea.org/divers-of-the-year/divers-of-the-year-2016/62746 |title=Beneath the Sea proudly presents \u2026The Class of 2016: Divers of the Year|website=beneaththesea.org|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref> and 2017 Pegasus Wings Awards for her lifetime achievements as an ocean conservationist. In 2019 she was awarded the Rob Stewart Foundation Lifetime Achievement for Ocean Conservation Award.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pegasusfoundation.org/2017-pegasus-wings-awards/ |title=2017 PEGASUS WINGS AWARDS|website=Pegasus Foundation|access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|-\n|2007\n|''The Shark Is Still Working: The Impact & Legacy of 'Jaws'''\n|Participant\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2007\n|''Diving Into 'Blue Water, White Death'''\n|Participant\n|Video documentary\n|-\n|2010\n|''Jaws: The Inside Story''\n|Herself\n|TV documentary\n|-\n|2012\n|''How \u2018Jaws\u2019 Changed the World''\n|Herself\n|TV documentary\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Work\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Nova (American TV program)|Nova]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"Why Sharks Attack\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2400254}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benchley, Wendy}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:Montclair High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:New Jersey city council members]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Pennington, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Skidmore College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Laurabowling", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wendy_Benchley"}
{"title_page": "Brunslar", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n| name         = Brunslar\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51|10|1|N|9|26|43|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| state        = Hesse\n| district     = Melsungen\n| elevation    = 154-273\n| area         = 16.41\n| population   = 2000\n| Stand        = 1974\n| dissolved    = 1 January 1974\n}}\n\n'''Brunslar''' was a short-lived [[municipality]] in North [[Hessen]], in the now-extinct [[Districts of Germany|district]] of [[Melsungen]], [[Germany]]. It was created during the changing of district boundaries on 1 February 1971, when the independent communities of [[Altenbrunslar]] and Neuenbrunslar fused. On the 31. December 1971 the community of [[Wolfershausen]] joined the Brunslar municipality.<ref name=Gemeindeverzeichnis1970bis1982>{{citation|editor-surname1=Statistisches Bundesamt|title=Historisches Gemeindeverzeichnis f\u00fcr die Bundesrepublik Deutschland. Namens-, Grenz- und Schl\u00fcsselnummern\u00e4nderungen bei Gemeinden, Kreisen und Regierungsbezirken vom 27. 5. 1970 bis 31. 12. 1982 |publisher=[[W. Kohlhammer]]|publication-place=Stuttgart und Mainz|pages=404 und 405|isbn=3-17-003263-1|date=  1983|language=German}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning the municipality covered an area of 1271 [[Hectare|ha]], in which approx. 1300 people lived. As the village of Wolfershausen was integrated, the area grew to 1641 ha and the population grew to approx. 2000.\n\nOn 1 January 1974 the municipality of Brunslar, together with the municipalities of Gensungen, Helmshausen, Hilgershausen und Rh\u00fcnda were included into the town of [[Felsberg (Hessen)|Felsberg]].<ref name= Gemeindeverzeichnis1970bis1982/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n| name         = Brunslar\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51|10|1|N|9|26|43|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| state        = Hesse\n| district     = Melsungen\n| elevation    = 154\n| elevationmax = 273\n| area         = 16.41\n| population   = 2000\n| Stand        = 1974\n| dissolved    = 1 January 1974\n}}\n\n'''Brunslar''' was a short-lived [[municipality]] in North [[Hessen]], in the now-extinct [[Districts of Germany|district]] of [[Melsungen]], [[Germany]]. It was created during the changing of district boundaries on 1 February 1971, when the independent communities of [[Altenbrunslar]] and Neuenbrunslar fused. On the 31. December 1971 the community of [[Wolfershausen]] joined the Brunslar municipality.<ref name=Gemeindeverzeichnis1970bis1982>{{citation|editor-surname1=Statistisches Bundesamt|title=Historisches Gemeindeverzeichnis f\u00fcr die Bundesrepublik Deutschland. Namens-, Grenz- und Schl\u00fcsselnummern\u00e4nderungen bei Gemeinden, Kreisen und Regierungsbezirken vom 27. 5. 1970 bis 31. 12. 1982 |publisher=[[W. Kohlhammer]]|publication-place=Stuttgart und Mainz|pages=404 und 405|isbn=3-17-003263-1|date=  1983|language=German}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning the municipality covered an area of 1271 [[Hectare|ha]], in which approx. 1300 people lived. As the village of Wolfershausen was integrated, the area grew to 1641 ha and the population grew to approx. 2000.\n\nOn 1 January 1974 the municipality of Brunslar, together with the municipalities of Gensungen, Helmshausen, Hilgershausen und Rh\u00fcnda were included into the town of [[Felsberg (Hessen)|Felsberg]].<ref name= Gemeindeverzeichnis1970bis1982/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brunslar"}
{"title_page": "Odessa High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Odessa High School\n|image          = Odessa_High_School_in_2009-(Front_showing_Auditorium)_2014-04-21_23-06.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|motto          = \n|established    = 1909\n|type           = Public\n|affiliation    = \n|district       = [[Ector County Independent School District]]\n|grades         = 9-12\n|principal      = Mauricio Marquez\n|Dean =\n|faculty        = \n|staff          = 222.81 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio          = 17.09<ref name=NCES/>\n|students       = \n|enrollment     = 3,807 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=4818000&SchoolPageNum=3&ID=481800001587|title=ODESSA H S|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|athletics      = \n|conference     = [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] Class 6A\n|colors         = {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}} Red(Scarlet) and White\n|mascot         = Broncho\n|rival          = [[Permian High School]]\n|campus_type    = AVID Demo. School\n|campus_size    = \n|free_label     = \n|free_text      = \n|free_label2    = \n|free_text2     = \n|free_label3    = \n|free_text3     = \n|streetaddress = 1301 N Dotsy\n|city = [[Odessa, Texas|Odessa]]\n|state = [[Texas|TX]]\n|zipcode = 79763-3576\n|country = [[United States]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|31|51|6.9|N|102|22|56.7|W|display=title}}\n|pushpin_map = Texas#USA\n|website = [http://www.ectorcountyisd.org/ode/site/default.asp Odessa High School]\n}}\n\n'''Odessa High School''' ('''OHS''') is a public [[high school]] located in [[Odessa, Texas]], United States.  It is one of three high schools in the [[Ector County Independent School District]]. The full name of the school is '''Odessa Senior High School'''. This name was originally to differentiate it from Odessa Junior High School (now known as David Crockett Middle School). Normally, the school is commonly referred to as Odessa High or just OHS.   In 2011, the school was rated \"Academically Acceptable\" by the [[Texas Education Agency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://ritter.tea.state.tx.us/perfreport/account/2011/index.html \n |title=2011 Accountability Rating System \n |publisher=Texas Education Agency \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628134123/http://ritter.tea.state.tx.us/perfreport/account/2011/index.html \n |archivedate=2012-06-28 \n}}</ref> On April 17, 2014 Odessa High School was named an AVID National Demonstration School.\n\nThe student body of Odessa High School is composed of freshmen (grade 9) through seniors (grade 12).  Freshmen are allowed to compete in varsity athletics with upper grades in all sports. However, this mainly happens in such sports as cross country, swimming, golf, gymnastics, tennis, volleyball, softball and baseball. To date, only one freshmen has competed on the varsity football team.its nasty\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Odessa Bronchos compete in the following sports:\n\n[[Cross country running|Cross country]], [[volleyball]], [[American football|football]], [[basketball]], [[powerlifting]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[Association football|soccer]], [[gymnastics]], [[golf]], [[tennis]], [[Track and field|track]], [[softball]], and [[baseball]].\n\n===State Titles===\n*Baseball <ref>[http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/baseball.php UIL Baseball Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210161440/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/baseball.php |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n**1950(All)\n*Football <ref>[http://lonestarfootball.net/team.asp?T=1650 Lone Star Football Network]</ref>\n**1946(2A)\n*Boys Track <ref>[http://www.uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-team.php?boys_girls=Boys UIL Boys Track Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017154529/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-team.php?boys_girls=Boys |date=2015-10-17 }}</ref>\n**1950(2A), 1951(2A), 1952(2A), 1992(5A)\n\n'''Odessa Blackshear''' - State Runners-up:  Basketball - 1953(PVIL-3A), 1954(PVIL-3A), 1955(PVIL-3A)\n\n==AVID Program==\nThe AVID program at OHS is a college preparation course for students. This program was recognized as a National Demonstration School as of April 17, 2014. The AVID committee decided unanimously on this decision. OHS is now a highly ranked AVID school. AVID has an on campus site team along with the AVID faculty. \n* AVID Coordinator- Rita Woodall\n* AVID Teacher/Asst. Coordinator - Naomi Fuentes\n* AVID Teacher - Tracey Borchardt\n* AVID Teacher - Kerina Joy\n\n==Mascot==\nThe mascot for Odessa High School is the Odessa Bronchos, with all female teams referred to as \"Lady Bronchos.\" This unique spelling of \"Broncho\" has resulted in Odessa High being the only high school in Texas with this particular mascot.<ref>[http://www.texasfootballratings.com/MascotwSchoolListAB.html Mascot School List A-B]</ref>  The original mascot for the team was the Yellowjackets and the team colors were purple and gold. In 1929, the student body voted 113-0 to change to the \"Bronchos\". The Bronchos colors were changed to scarlet and white.\n\n== Band ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=January 2010}}\nThe Odessa High School band has the longest consecutive streak of first division rating in marching contests in the State of Texas, going back 81 years. <ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.myplainview.com/articles/2009/10/18/breaking_news/doc4ada824865bf6440230887.txt|publisher=[[Plainview Daily Herald]]|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The band has also been invited to various music festival and contests across the nation. In March 2007, the band was invited to play their marching season selections \"Letters from the Front\" at the [[National World War II Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] In 2004, The Odessa High School Band combined with the band from [[Permian High School]] in Odessa to form one of the largest bands ever to march in the [[Tournament of Roses Parade]] in [[Pasadena, California]] (over 500 members).{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\nThe OHS Band was started in 1932 under the direction of G. Ward Moody. Directors Robert L. Maddox and Bill Dean have been the longest tenured directors of the band with 13 years and 22 years respectively. As of July 2018, John Mayo is the director of the band.<ref>{{cite news |title=OHS band director is familiar face |url=https://www.oaoa.com/news/education/ecisd/article_ead2e8c2-854a-11e8-9126-73e43ffcdb6a.html |accessdate=31 October 2019 |agency=AIM Media TX LLC |publisher=OA Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=OHS band optimistic about marching season |url=https://www.oaoa.com/news/education/ecisd/article_1b5a6cfa-b4b0-11e9-b23e-ffa95148463d.html |accessdate=31 October 2019 |agency=OA Online |publisher=AIM Media TX LLC}}</ref> The Instrumental Music Building at OHS is named in honor of Maddox and the main band hall is named in honor of Dean.\n\nFrom 1981 through 2006, the band has had at least one member make the Texas All State Band each year. In the 1998-99 school year, eight members were accorded All State honors. Band members also consistently do well at UIL Solo and Ensemble contest.\n\n==Culture==\nOdessa High School students reported ghost sightings and paranormal phenomena at the school for decades, up to 2006, centering around Betty Williams, who was killed during the \"[[Kiss and Kill]]\" homicide in 1961. Mack Herring, her killer, was ruled not guilty by grounds of temporary insanity by a Texas jury as she had asked Herring to kill her. Odessa High's administration applied paint to the school auditorium's windows to counter the ghost story culture.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Colloff, Pamela|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/a-kiss-before-dying/|title=A Kiss Before Dying|magazine=[[Texas Monthly]]|date=February 2006|accessdate=2019-01-14}}</ref> In 2019 CBS 7 Odessa stated \"Many believe her ghost still haunts the halls of Odessa High School to this day.\"<ref name=Herringdied>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbs7.com/content/news/FIRST-ON-CBS7-Kiss-and-Kill-killer-has-died-504111961.html|title=FIRST ON CBS7: \"Kiss and Kill\" killer has died|publisher=CBS 7|date=2019-01-09|accessdate=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n*[[Gene Babb]], linebacker and fullback for [[San Francisco 49ers]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]]<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BabbGe20.htm</ref>\n*[[Marcus Cannon]], offensive tackle for [[Texas Christian University|TCU]] and [[New England Patriots]]\n*[[Hayden Fry]], former head football coach, [[Southern Methodist University]], [[University of North Texas]], [[University of Iowa]]\n*[[Larry Gatlin|Larry Gatlin, Steve Gatlin, and Rudy Gatlin]] &mdash; [[Grammy Award]]-winning country artists\n*[[Ronnie Goodwin]], football player, [[Baylor University]] and [[Philadelphia Eagles]] 1963-68<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=GOODWRON01 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610084825/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=GOODWRON01 |archivedate=2011-06-10 }} Ronnie Goodwin stats</ref>\n*[[Bradley Marquez]], Texas Tech football player and minor league baseball outfielder, professional football player for [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n*[[Nolan McCarty]], class of 1986, Chair Department of Politics, [[Princeton University]]\n*[[Bellinda Myrick]], class of 1966, Miss Texas 1970, Miss West Texas 1970, Miss America USO Show (one of 7 women) touring South Vietnam during war visiting U.S. military; singer, actress, toured with [[Bob Hope]]\n*[[Derrick Shepard (wide receiver)|Derrick Shepard]], wide receiver for [[University of Oklahoma]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]]<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/ShepDe00.htm</ref>\n*Jack Ward, class of 1966, bareback riding champion with two World Championships (1977 and 1978); inducted into Texas Cowboy Hall of Fame on January 13, 2011 in Fort Worth\n*[[Stephnie Weir]], actress, ''[[Mad TV]]''\n*[[Buddy West|George E. \"Buddy\" West]] (1936\u20132008), Odessa's representative to [[Texas Legislature]], 1993-2008<ref name=WestTXlegis>{{cite web\n |accessdate=2007-10-31 \n |url=http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/dist81/west.htm \n |title=Representative G.E. Buddy West \n |publisher=Texas House of Representatives \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611221717/http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/dist81/west.htm \n |archivedate=2007-06-11 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n*[[Alfred M. Wilson]], USMC, class of 1967<ref name=1967alum>{{cite web|accessdate=2007-10-30 |url=http://www.odessahighschool-classof1967.org/inmemorium.html |work=Odessa High School &mdash; Class of 1967 |title=In Memoriam |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216134642/http://www.odessahighschool-classof1967.org/inmemorium.html |archivedate=February 16, 2007 }}</ref>&mdash; posthumous [[Medal of Honor]], [[Killed in action|KIA]] in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]<ref name=WW_USMC>{{cite web|accessdate=2007-10-07 \n |url = http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/Wilson_AM.htm\n  |title = Private First Class Alfred M. Wilson, Medal of Honor recipient\n  |work = Who's who in Marine Corps history\n  |publisher = History Division, United States Marine Corps}}</ref>\n*[[Richard Wortham]], college baseball star at [[University of Texas]] and former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://theshadowlands.net/places/texas2.htm The Real Story About Elizabeth]\n*[http://www.ectorcountyisd.org/domain/2165 Odessa High School website]\n*[http://www.odessaband.org/ OHS Band]\n*[http://www.bronchofootball.com Odessa High Football]\n*[http://www.odessahigh.com/ Odessa High School Alumni website]\n*[http://www.texasbob.com/fb_stategame.html Odessa High School vs. San Antonio Jefferson 1946 State Championship Game] - TexasBob.com\n*[http://www.texasbob.com/travel/tbt_ratliff.html Ratliff Stadium - TexasBob.com]\n{{Odessa, Texas}}\n{{UIL District 3-5A High Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Ector County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Odessa, Texas]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Odessa High School\n|image          = Odessa_High_School_in_2009-(Front_showing_Auditorium)_2014-04-21_23-06.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|motto          = \n|established    = 1909\n|type           = Public\n|affiliation    = \n|district       = [[Ector County Independent School District]]\n|grades         = 9-12\n|principal      = Mauricio Marquez\n|Dean =\n|faculty        = \n|staff          = 222.81 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio          = 17.09<ref name=NCES/>\n|students       = \n|enrollment     = 3,807 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=4818000&SchoolPageNum=3&ID=481800001587|title=ODESSA H S|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|athletics      = \n|conference     = [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] Class 6A\n|colors         = {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}} Red(Scarlet) and White\n|mascot         = Broncho\n|rival          = [[Permian High School]]\n|campus_type    = AVID Demo. School\n|campus_size    = \n|free_label     = \n|free_text      = \n|free_label2    = \n|free_text2     = \n|free_label3    = \n|free_text3     = \n|streetaddress = 1301 N Dotsy\n|city = [[Odessa, Texas|Odessa]]\n|state = [[Texas|TX]]\n|zipcode = 79763-3576\n|country = [[United States]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|31|51|6.9|N|102|22|56.7|W|display=title}}\n|pushpin_map = Texas#USA\n|website = [http://www.ectorcountyisd.org/ode/site/default.asp Odessa High School]\n}}\n\n'''Odessa High School''' ('''OHS''') is a public [[high school]] located in [[Odessa, Texas]], United States.  It is one of three high schools in the [[Ector County Independent School District]]. The full name of the school is '''Odessa Senior High School'''. This name was originally to differentiate it from Odessa Junior High School (now known as David Crockett Middle School). Normally, the school is commonly referred to as Odessa High or just OHS.   In 2011, the school was rated \"Academically Acceptable\" by the [[Texas Education Agency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://ritter.tea.state.tx.us/perfreport/account/2011/index.html \n |title=2011 Accountability Rating System \n |publisher=Texas Education Agency \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628134123/http://ritter.tea.state.tx.us/perfreport/account/2011/index.html \n |archivedate=2012-06-28 \n}}</ref> On April 17, 2014 Odessa High School was named an AVID National Demonstration School.\n\nThe student body of Odessa High School is composed of freshmen (grade 9) through seniors (grade 12).  Freshmen are allowed to compete in varsity athletics with upper grades in all sports. However, this mainly happens in such sports as cross country, swimming, golf, gymnastics, tennis, volleyball, softball and baseball. To date, only one freshmen has competed on the varsity football team.\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Odessa Bronchos compete in the following sports:\n\n[[Cross country running|Cross country]], [[volleyball]], [[American football|football]], [[basketball]], [[powerlifting]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[Association football|soccer]], [[gymnastics]], [[golf]], [[tennis]], [[Track and field|track]], [[softball]], and [[baseball]].\n\n===State Titles===\n*Baseball <ref>[http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/baseball.php UIL Baseball Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210161440/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/baseball.php |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n**1950(All)\n*Football <ref>[http://lonestarfootball.net/team.asp?T=1650 Lone Star Football Network]</ref>\n**1946(2A)\n*Boys Track <ref>[http://www.uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-team.php?boys_girls=Boys UIL Boys Track Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017154529/http://uil100.org/archives/athletics/track-field-team.php?boys_girls=Boys |date=2015-10-17 }}</ref>\n**1950(2A), 1951(2A), 1952(2A), 1992(5A)\n\n'''Odessa Blackshear''' - State Runners-up:  Basketball - 1953(PVIL-3A), 1954(PVIL-3A), 1955(PVIL-3A)\n\n==AVID Program==\nThe AVID program at OHS is a college preparation course for students. This program was recognized as a National Demonstration School as of April 17, 2014. The AVID committee decided unanimously on this decision. OHS is now a highly ranked AVID school. AVID has an on campus site team along with the AVID faculty. \n* AVID Coordinator- Rita Woodall\n* AVID Teacher/Asst. Coordinator - Naomi Fuentes\n* AVID Teacher - Tracey Borchardt\n* AVID Teacher - Kerina Joy\n\n==Mascot==\nThe mascot for Odessa High School is the Odessa Bronchos, with all female teams referred to as \"Lady Bronchos.\" This unique spelling of \"Broncho\" has resulted in Odessa High being the only high school in Texas with this particular mascot.<ref>[http://www.texasfootballratings.com/MascotwSchoolListAB.html Mascot School List A-B]</ref>  The original mascot for the team was the Yellowjackets and the team colors were purple and gold. In 1929, the student body voted 113-0 to change to the \"Bronchos\". The Bronchos colors were changed to scarlet and white.\n\n== Band ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=January 2010}}\nThe Odessa High School band has the longest consecutive streak of first division rating in marching contests in the State of Texas, going back 81 years. <ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.myplainview.com/articles/2009/10/18/breaking_news/doc4ada824865bf6440230887.txt|publisher=[[Plainview Daily Herald]]|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The band has also been invited to various music festival and contests across the nation. In March 2007, the band was invited to play their marching season selections \"Letters from the Front\" at the [[National World War II Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] In 2004, The Odessa High School Band combined with the band from [[Permian High School]] in Odessa to form one of the largest bands ever to march in the [[Tournament of Roses Parade]] in [[Pasadena, California]] (over 500 members).{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\nThe OHS Band was started in 1932 under the direction of G. Ward Moody. Directors Robert L. Maddox and Bill Dean have been the longest tenured directors of the band with 13 years and 22 years respectively. As of July 2018, John Mayo is the director of the band.<ref>{{cite news |title=OHS band director is familiar face |url=https://www.oaoa.com/news/education/ecisd/article_ead2e8c2-854a-11e8-9126-73e43ffcdb6a.html |accessdate=31 October 2019 |agency=AIM Media TX LLC |publisher=OA Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=OHS band optimistic about marching season |url=https://www.oaoa.com/news/education/ecisd/article_1b5a6cfa-b4b0-11e9-b23e-ffa95148463d.html |accessdate=31 October 2019 |agency=OA Online |publisher=AIM Media TX LLC}}</ref> The Instrumental Music Building at OHS is named in honor of Maddox and the main band hall is named in honor of Dean.\n\nFrom 1981 through 2006, the band has had at least one member make the Texas All State Band each year. In the 1998-99 school year, eight members were accorded All State honors. Band members also consistently do well at UIL Solo and Ensemble contest.\n\n==Culture==\nOdessa High School students reported ghost sightings and paranormal phenomena at the school for decades, up to 2006, centering around Betty Williams, who was killed during the \"[[Kiss and Kill]]\" homicide in 1961. Mack Herring, her killer, was ruled not guilty by grounds of temporary insanity by a Texas jury as she had asked Herring to kill her. Odessa High's administration applied paint to the school auditorium's windows to counter the ghost story culture.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Colloff, Pamela|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/a-kiss-before-dying/|title=A Kiss Before Dying|magazine=[[Texas Monthly]]|date=February 2006|accessdate=2019-01-14}}</ref> In 2019 CBS 7 Odessa stated \"Many believe her ghost still haunts the halls of Odessa High School to this day.\"<ref name=Herringdied>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbs7.com/content/news/FIRST-ON-CBS7-Kiss-and-Kill-killer-has-died-504111961.html|title=FIRST ON CBS7: \"Kiss and Kill\" killer has died|publisher=CBS 7|date=2019-01-09|accessdate=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n*[[Gene Babb]], linebacker and fullback for [[San Francisco 49ers]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]]<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BabbGe20.htm</ref>\n*[[Marcus Cannon]], offensive tackle for [[Texas Christian University|TCU]] and [[New England Patriots]]\n*[[Hayden Fry]], former head football coach, [[Southern Methodist University]], [[University of North Texas]], [[University of Iowa]]\n*[[Larry Gatlin|Larry Gatlin, Steve Gatlin, and Rudy Gatlin]] &mdash; [[Grammy Award]]-winning country artists\n*[[Ronnie Goodwin]], football player, [[Baylor University]] and [[Philadelphia Eagles]] 1963-68<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=GOODWRON01 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610084825/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=GOODWRON01 |archivedate=2011-06-10 }} Ronnie Goodwin stats</ref>\n*[[Bradley Marquez]], Texas Tech football player and minor league baseball outfielder, professional football player for [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n*[[Nolan McCarty]], class of 1986, Chair Department of Politics, [[Princeton University]]\n*[[Bellinda Myrick]], class of 1966, Miss Texas 1970, Miss West Texas 1970, Miss America USO Show (one of 7 women) touring South Vietnam during war visiting U.S. military; singer, actress, toured with [[Bob Hope]]\n*[[Derrick Shepard (wide receiver)|Derrick Shepard]], wide receiver for [[University of Oklahoma]] and [[Dallas Cowboys]]<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/ShepDe00.htm</ref>\n*Jack Ward, class of 1966, bareback riding champion with two World Championships (1977 and 1978); inducted into Texas Cowboy Hall of Fame on January 13, 2011 in Fort Worth\n*[[Stephnie Weir]], actress, ''[[Mad TV]]''\n*[[Buddy West|George E. \"Buddy\" West]] (1936\u20132008), Odessa's representative to [[Texas Legislature]], 1993-2008<ref name=WestTXlegis>{{cite web\n |accessdate=2007-10-31 \n |url=http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/dist81/west.htm \n |title=Representative G.E. Buddy West \n |publisher=Texas House of Representatives \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611221717/http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/dist81/west.htm \n |archivedate=2007-06-11 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n*[[Alfred M. Wilson]], USMC, class of 1967<ref name=1967alum>{{cite web|accessdate=2007-10-30 |url=http://www.odessahighschool-classof1967.org/inmemorium.html |work=Odessa High School &mdash; Class of 1967 |title=In Memoriam |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216134642/http://www.odessahighschool-classof1967.org/inmemorium.html |archivedate=February 16, 2007 }}</ref>&mdash; posthumous [[Medal of Honor]], [[Killed in action|KIA]] in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]<ref name=WW_USMC>{{cite web|accessdate=2007-10-07 \n |url = http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/Wilson_AM.htm\n  |title = Private First Class Alfred M. Wilson, Medal of Honor recipient\n  |work = Who's who in Marine Corps history\n  |publisher = History Division, United States Marine Corps}}</ref>\n*[[Richard Wortham]], college baseball star at [[University of Texas]] and former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://theshadowlands.net/places/texas2.htm The Real Story About Elizabeth]\n*[http://www.ectorcountyisd.org/